{"title_page": "John Butterfill", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sir John Butterfill\n| image = \n| caption =  \n| constituency_MP = [[Bournemouth West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth West]]\n| parliament = \n| term_start = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|10 June 1983]]\n| term_end = [[2010 United Kingdom general election|12 April 2010]]\n| majority =\n| predecessor = [[John Eden, Baron Eden of Winton|John Eden]]\n| successor = [[Conor Burns]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|02|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingston upon Thames]], [[Surrey]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Pamela Ross-Symons\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Surveyor<br />Business executive\n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Sir John Valentine Butterfill''' [[FRICS]] (born 14 February 1941) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]]. He was the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bournemouth West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth West]] from [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] until he stood down at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Surrey, Butterfill was educated at [[Caterham School]] and the [[College of Estate Management]] in London. In 1962 he began his career as a valuer with Jones Laing Wootton, before becoming a senior executive with the [[Hammerson]] Group in 1964. He was a director at the Audley Properties Group (now the [[Bovis Homes Group]]) from 1969 until he became the [[Managing Director]] of the St Paul's Securities Group. He became a [[Fellow (society)|Fellow]] of the [[Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors]] in 1974. He was elected as the Chairman of the [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] Conservative Association from 1976\u20131982. In 1977 he became a senior partner in Curchod & Co Chartered [[surveying|Surveyors]], where he remained until 1992. He was Director of ISLEF Building and Construction Ltd from 1985\u201391, and of the Pavilion Services Group from 1992\u20134.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn 1979 Butterfill contested [[London]] South East Inner at the [[European Parliament]]ary election but was defeated comfortably by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour's]] Richard Balfe. He was selected to contest the [[1981 Croydon North West by-election|Croydon North West by-election]] in 1981 which was caused by the death of Conservative MP [[Robert Taylor (UK politician)|Robert Taylor]]. It came as a great surprise when [[Bill Pitt (politician)|Bill Pitt]] won the seat for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], on a 24% swing and with a majority of 3,254. He was subsequently chosen to contest the south coast seat of Bournemouth West on the retirement of the veteran MP [[John Eden, Baron Eden of Winton|John Eden]]. Butterfill won the seat at the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]] with a majority of 13,331, and remained the MP there until 2010.\n\nButterfill remained a [[backbencher]] for the entirety of his [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|parliamentary]] career. He was the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] PPS to the [[Secretary of State for Energy]] [[Cecil Parkinson]] in 1988, remaining Parkinson's PPS when he became the [[Secretary of State for Transport]] in 1989. His job ended when Parkinson resigned from the [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet]] at the election of [[John Major]] to succeed [[Margaret Thatcher]] in 1990.\n\nButterfill has served on many [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|select committee]]s during his more than 20 year [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]] career. He has been responsible for introducing many [[Act of Parliament|Acts of Parliament]] including the Registered Homes (Amendment) Act 1991;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1991/Ukpga_19910020_en_1.htm|title=Registered Homes (Amendment) Act 1991|publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> the [[Insolvency]] (Amendment) Act 1994;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1994/Ukpga_19940007_en_1.htm |title=Insolvency Act 1994 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> and the Policy Holders Protection Act 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1997/1997018.htm |title=UK Public General Acts |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date=23 May 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> He has recently been noted for campaigning for an increase in parliamentary pay and been quoted in the press as saying that \"there are a lot of unhappy bunnies\" in relation to MP's remuneration.\n\nIn 1995, he entered a bill to place the UK in the [[Central European Time]]. It was opposed by many Scottish MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/otr/intext95-96/Daylight14.1.96.html |title= On The Record - Interviews |work=BBC Online|publisher=BBC |date=21 December 1996 |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe introduced the Financial Mutuals Arrangements Bill which was renamed and became the [[Building Societies (Funding) and Mutual Societies (Transfers) Act 2007]].\n\n===Expenses===\n{{Main|Disclosure of expenses of British Members of Parliament}}\n\nIn May 2009, as part of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'''s publication of details, the newspaper revealed that for five years, Butterfill owned a six-bedroom country house in [[Woking]], [[Surrey]], 80 miles from his constituency. At the time, he designated a small flat in his Bournemouth constituency, bought for \u00a356,000, as his \"main home.\" Said by Butterfill to have been bought as a wreck, he submitted regular claims under the second home allowance for the cost of running the Woking house, which had a swimming pool and extensive grounds. This included \u00a317,000 on servants\u2019 quarters alone, contributing up to \u00a31,778 a month towards the mortgage interest, and was also reimbursed for [[council tax]] bills for the \"staff annex\", where his [[Housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeeper]] and odd job man lived.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5396199/MPs-expenses-Tory-MP-Sir-John-Butterfill-paid-no-tax-on-600000-house-profit.html|title=MPs' expenses: Tory MP Sir John Butterfill paid no tax on \u00a3600,000 house profit|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=27 May 2009|accessdate=27 May 2009 | location=London | first=Rosa | last=Prince}}</ref>\n\nButterfill repaid \u00a317,479 in discretionary repayments to the government related to the expenses row.  However, Butterfill was only over-paid by a total of \u00a32,032.47 for mortgage interest (\u00a31,408 in 2006-07 and \u00a3625 in 2008-09). He was also overpaid by a total of \u00a3332 for council tax in 2005-06 (of which \u00a347.66 was due to payments not being reduced for dissolution, and \u00a3284.00 due to an incorrect adjustment when moving house). Total repayment recommended was \u00a32,364.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|title=Review of past ACA payments|publisher=House of Commons|accessdate=30 April 2014 | location=London | date=2 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nButterfill is one of the 98 MPs who voted to keep their expense details secret.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1816072.ece|title=how your MP voted on the FOI Bill|publisher=times online|accessdate=30 May 2009 | location=London | date=20 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n==''Dispatches'' Lobbyist investigation ==\n{{main|2010 cash for influence scandal}}\nButterfill was one of the MPs named in the 2010 [[sting operation]]. Butterfill is alleged to have told an undercover reporter that he would [[lobbying|lobby]] to benefit the fictitious company and use his political connections for a payment of \u00a335000 a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/03/21/tory-mp-sir-john-butterfill-offered-access-to-chiefs-for-35-000-115875-22127197|title=Tory MP Sir John Butterfill offered access to chiefs for \u00a335,000|publisher=[[Daily Mirror|The Daily Mirror]]|date=21 March 2010|accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref> Butterfill was also seen on the programme saying he had been one of the four people who persuaded David Cameron to stand for leader of the Conservative party and that it was likely that he (Butterfill) would be made a [[peerage|peer]] and go to the [[House of Lords]]. The following day the leader of the Conservative Party, David Cameron said, \"I can tell you that is not going to happen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23818081-cameron-dashes-tory-butterfills-peerage-hopes-after-lobby-firm-boasts.do |title=Cameron dashes Tory Butterfill's peerage hopes after 'lobby firm boasts' |publisher=[[The London Evening Standard]] |date=23 March 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326203601/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23818081-cameron-dashes-tory-butterfills-peerage-hopes-after-lobby-firm-boasts.do |archivedate=26 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn the final report of the [[Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards|Standards Commissioner]] it was deemed that Butterfill did not breach Parliamentary rules. \u201cThe Commissioner does not consider that any of the statements made by Sir John during the course of his meeting with the undercover reporter or any of the actions he took as a Member referred to in his statements were in breach of the rules of the House. He has not, therefore, upheld the allegations against Sir John.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmstnprv/654/654.pdf|title=Committee on Standards and Privileges Sir John Butterfill, Mr Stephen Byers, Ms Patricia Hewitt, Mr Geoff Hoon, Mr Richard Caborn and Mr Adam Ingram - Ninth Report of Session 2010\u201311 |publisher=[[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|date=7 December 2010|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Pamela Ross-Symons in 1965 in Surrey and they have a son and three daughters.  He was awarded a [[Knight Bachelor|knighthood]] in 2003 for 'services to Parliament'. He is also a businessman and is a director and adviser to many companies, and is council member of the [[People's Dispensary for Sick Animals]]. His constituency included the centre of [[Bournemouth]]. He speaks [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Danish language|Danish]] and [[French language|French]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100326105951/http://www.johnbutterfillmp.co.uk/ Official Website]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-775,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: John Butterfill MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/john_butterfill/bournemouth_west TheyWorkForYou.com - John Butterfill MP]\n* [http://www.bournemouthwestconservatives.com/ Bournemouth West Conservatives]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/80.stm BBC Politics Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Eden, Baron Eden of Winton|Sir John Eden, Bt]] }}\n{{ s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Bournemouth West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth West]]\n | years = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Conor Burns]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the British House of Commons election, 2000}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butterfill, John}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Caterham School]]\n[[Category:Politics of Dorset]]\n[[Category:People from Kingston upon Thames]]\n[[Category:People from Bournemouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sir John Butterfill\n| image = \n| caption =  \n| constituency_MP = [[Bournemouth West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth West]]\n| parliament = \n| term_start = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|10 June 1983]]\n| term_end = [[2010 United Kingdom general election|12 April 2010]]\n| majority =\n| predecessor = [[John Eden, Baron Eden of Winton|John Eden]]\n| successor = [[Conor Burns]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|02|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingston upon Thames]], [[Surrey]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Pamela Ross-Symons\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Surveyor<br />Business executive\n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Sir John Valentine Butterfill''' [[FRICS]] (born 14 February 1941) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]]. He was the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bournemouth West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth West]] from [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] until he stood down at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Surrey, Butterfill was educated at [[Caterham School]] and the [[College of Estate Management]] in London. In 1962 he began his career as a valuer with Jones Laing Wootton, before becoming a senior executive with the [[Hammerson]] Group in 1964. He was a director at the Audley Properties Group (now the [[Bovis Homes Group]]) from 1969 until he became the [[Managing Director]] of the St Paul's Securities Group. He became a [[Fellow (society)|Fellow]] of the [[Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors]] in 1974. He was elected as the Chairman of the [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] Conservative Association from 1976-1982. In 1977 he became a senior partner in Curchod & Co Chartered [[surveying|Surveyors]], where he remained until 1992. He was Director of ISLEF Building and Construction Ltd from 1985\u201391, and of the Pavilion Services Group from 1992-4.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn 1979 Butterfill contested [[London]] South East Inner at the [[European Parliament]]ary election but was defeated comfortably by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour's]] Richard Balfe. He was selected to contest the [[1981 Croydon North West by-election|Croydon North West by-election]] in 1981 which was caused by the death of Conservative MP [[Robert Taylor (UK politician)|Robert Taylor]]. It came as a great surprise when [[Bill Pitt (politician)|Bill Pitt]] won the seat for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], on a 24% swing and with a majority of 3,254. He was subsequently chosen to contest the south coast seat of Bournemouth West on the retirement of the veteran MP [[John Eden, Baron Eden of Winton|John Eden]]. Butterfill won the seat at the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]] with a majority of 13,331, and remained the MP there until 2010.\n\nButterfill remained a [[backbencher]] for the entirety of his [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|parliamentary]] career. He was the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] PPS to the [[Secretary of State for Energy]] [[Cecil Parkinson]] in 1988, remaining Parkinson's PPS when he became the [[Secretary of State for Transport]] in 1989. His job ended when Parkinson resigned from the [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet]] at the election of [[John Major]] to succeed [[Margaret Thatcher]] in 1990.\n\nButterfill has served on many [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|select committee]]s during his more than 20 year [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]] career. He has been responsible for introducing many [[Act of Parliament|Acts of Parliament]] including the Registered Homes (Amendment) Act 1991;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1991/Ukpga_19910020_en_1.htm|title=Registered Homes (Amendment) Act 1991|publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> the [[Insolvency]] (Amendment) Act 1994;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1994/Ukpga_19940007_en_1.htm |title=Insolvency Act 1994 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> and the Policy Holders Protection Act 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1997/1997018.htm |title=UK Public General Acts |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date=23 May 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> He has recently been noted for campaigning for an increase in parliamentary pay and been quoted in the press as saying that \"there are a lot of unhappy bunnies\" in relation to MP's remuneration.\n\nIn 1995, he entered a bill to place the UK in the [[Central European Time]]. It was opposed by many Scottish MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/otr/intext95-96/Daylight14.1.96.html |title= On The Record - Interviews |work=BBC Online|publisher=BBC |date=21 December 1996 |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe introduced the Financial Mutuals Arrangements Bill which was renamed and became the [[Building Societies (Funding) and Mutual Societies (Transfers) Act 2007]].\n\n===Expenses===\n{{Main|Disclosure of expenses of British Members of Parliament}}\n\nIn May 2009, as part of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'''s publication of details, the newspaper revealed that for five years, Butterfill owned a six-bedroom country house in [[Woking]], [[Surrey]], 80 miles from his constituency. At the time, he designated a small flat in his Bournemouth constituency, bought for \u00a356,000, as his \"main home.\" Said by Butterfill to have been bought as a wreck, he submitted regular claims under the second home allowance for the cost of running the Woking house, which had a swimming pool and extensive grounds. This included \u00a317,000 on servants\u2019 quarters alone, contributing up to \u00a31,778 a month towards the mortgage interest, and was also reimbursed for [[council tax]] bills for the \"staff annex\", where his [[Housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeeper]] and odd job man lived.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5396199/MPs-expenses-Tory-MP-Sir-John-Butterfill-paid-no-tax-on-600000-house-profit.html|title=MPs' expenses: Tory MP Sir John Butterfill paid no tax on \u00a3600,000 house profit|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=27 May 2009|accessdate=27 May 2009 | location=London | first=Rosa | last=Prince}}</ref>\n\nButterfill repaid \u00a317,479 in discretionary repayments to the government related to the expenses row.  However, Butterfill was only over-paid by a total of \u00a32,032.47 for mortgage interest (\u00a31,408 in 2006-07 and \u00a3625 in 2008-09). He was also overpaid by a total of \u00a3332 for council tax in 2005-06 (of which \u00a347.66 was due to payments not being reduced for dissolution, and \u00a3284.00 due to an incorrect adjustment when moving house). Total repayment recommended was \u00a32,364.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|title=Review of past ACA payments|publisher=House of Commons|accessdate=30 April 2014 | location=London | date=2 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nButterfill is one of the 98 MPs who voted to keep their expense details secret.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1816072.ece|title=how your MP voted on the FOI Bill|publisher=times online|accessdate=30 May 2009 | location=London | date=20 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n==''Dispatches'' Lobbyist investigation ==\n{{main|2010 cash for influence scandal}}\nButterfill was one of the MPs named in the 2010 [[sting operation]]. Butterfill is alleged to have told an undercover reporter that he would [[lobbying|lobby]] to benefit the fictitious company and use his political connections for a payment of \u00a335000 a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/03/21/tory-mp-sir-john-butterfill-offered-access-to-chiefs-for-35-000-115875-22127197|title=Tory MP Sir John Butterfill offered access to chiefs for \u00a335,000|publisher=[[Daily Mirror|The Daily Mirror]]|date=21 March 2010|accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref> Butterfill was also seen on the programme saying he had been one of the four people who persuaded David Cameron to stand for leader of the Conservative party and that it was likely that he (Butterfill) would be made a [[peerage|peer]] and go to the [[House of Lords]]. The following day the leader of the Conservative Party, David Cameron said, \"I can tell you that is not going to happen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23818081-cameron-dashes-tory-butterfills-peerage-hopes-after-lobby-firm-boasts.do |title=Cameron dashes Tory Butterfill's peerage hopes after 'lobby firm boasts' |publisher=[[The London Evening Standard]] |date=23 March 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326203601/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23818081-cameron-dashes-tory-butterfills-peerage-hopes-after-lobby-firm-boasts.do |archivedate=26 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn the final report of the [[Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards|Standards Commissioner]] it was deemed that Butterfill did not breach Parliamentary rules. \u201cThe Commissioner does not consider that any of the statements made by Sir John during the course of his meeting with the undercover reporter or any of the actions he took as a Member referred to in his statements were in breach of the rules of the House. He has not, therefore, upheld the allegations against Sir John.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmstnprv/654/654.pdf|title=Committee on Standards and Privileges Sir John Butterfill, Mr Stephen Byers, Ms Patricia Hewitt, Mr Geoff Hoon, Mr Richard Caborn and Mr Adam Ingram - Ninth Report of Session 2010\u201311 |publisher=[[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|date=7 December 2010|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Pamela Ross-Symons in 1965 in Surrey and they have a son and three daughters.  He was awarded a [[Knight Bachelor|knighthood]] in 2003 for 'services to Parliament'. He is also a businessman and is a director and adviser to many companies, and is council member of the [[People's Dispensary for Sick Animals]]. His constituency included the centre of [[Bournemouth]]. He speaks [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Danish language|Danish]] and [[French language|French]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100326105951/http://www.johnbutterfillmp.co.uk/ Official Website]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-775,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: John Butterfill MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/john_butterfill/bournemouth_west TheyWorkForYou.com - John Butterfill MP]\n* [http://www.bournemouthwestconservatives.com/ Bournemouth West Conservatives]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/80.stm BBC Politics Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Eden, Baron Eden of Winton|Sir John Eden, Bt]] }}\n{{ s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Bournemouth West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth West]]\n | years = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u20