{"title_page": "Kennedy Stewart (Canadian politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian politician and academic}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox CanadianMP \n| honorific-prefix = [[His Worship]]\n| name = Kennedy Stewart\n| image = Kennedy-Stewart-MP.jpg\n| birth_name = Edward Charles Kennedy Stewart\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|11|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| profession = {{hlist|Politician|academic}}\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n| otherparty = [[New Democratic Party|New Democratic]]\n| residence = [[Vancouver]], British Columbia\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Acadia University]]\n* [[Simon Fraser University]]\n* [[London School of Economics]]\n}}\n| office1 = 40th [[Mayor of Vancouver]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Gregor Robertson (politician)|Gregor Robertson]] \n| term_start1 = November 5, 2018\n| office2 = Member of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]]<br/>for [[Burnaby South]]\n| term_start2 = October 19, 2015\n| term_end2 = September 14, 2018\n| predecessor2 = ''Riding established''\n| successor2 = [[Jagmeet Singh]]\n| office3 = Member of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]]<br/>for [[Burnaby\u2014Douglas]]\n| term_start3 = May 2, 2011\n| term_end3 = October 19, 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[Bill Siksay]]\n| successor3 = ''Riding dissolved''\n| office4 = NDP Science Critic\n| term_start4 = June 19, 2012\n| term_end4 = September 14, 2018\n| predecessor4 = [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne LeBlanc]]\n| successor4 = TBD\n\n| office5 = NDP BC Caucus Chair\n| term_start5 = December 9, 2015\n| term_end5 = September 14, 2018\n| predecessor5 = [[Murray Rankin]]\n| successor5 = TBD\n\n| spouse = Jeanette Ashe\n| website = {{URL|https://www.kennedystewart.ca/}}\n| footnotes=\n}}\n\n'''Edward Charles Kennedy Stewart''' (born November 8, 1966) is a Canadian politician and academic serving as the 40th and current [[List of mayors of Vancouver|mayor of Vancouver]] since 2018.<ref name=\"swearing in\">{{cite news |last1=Fumano |first1=Dan |title=Collegiality reigns as Vancouver's new council starts work |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/vancouvers-new-mayor-and-council-to-be-sworn-in-monday-afternoon |access-date=November 7, 2018 |work=Vancouver Sun |date=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-vancouver-mayor-kennedy-stewart-calls-for-ubc-subway-project-to-be-in/ \"Vancouver Mayor Kennedy Stewart calls for UBC subway project to be in service by 2030\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', January 23, 2019.</ref> He previously was the [[member of Parliament]] (MP) for the riding of [[Burnaby\u2014Douglas]] (2011\u20132015) and [[Burnaby South]] (2015\u20132018), serving in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] as a member of the [[New Democratic Party]] (NDP) caucus.<ref name=\"parlbio\">[http://www.parl.gc.ca/parlinfo/Files/Parliamentarian.aspx?Item=eb8710eb-e6dd-4c04-9d9a-60e7c8503565&Language=E&Section=ALL \"Kennedy Stewart bio\"]. Parliament of Canada Biography.</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Stewart announced his pending resignation from Parliament, in order to seek election as Mayor of Vancouver as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"mayor\">{{cite news |last=Laanela |first=Mike |title=Kennedy Stewart confirms he will run for mayor of Vancouver as independent |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/kennedy-stewart-running-for-vancouver-mayor-1.4657199 |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> In August 2018, he publicly released his letter to the Speaker of House, [[Geoff Regan]], confirming his resignation, effective September 14, 2018. During the [[2018 Vancouver municipal election]], Stewart was declared the winner of the mayoral race by a margin of fewer than 1,000 votes over Ken Sim, the [[Non-Partisan Association]] (NPA) candidate.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://vancouver.ca/your-government/election-results-2018-table.aspx |title=Election results - table |last=Vancouver |first=City of |date=October 20, 2018 |website=vancouver.ca |access-date=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nStewart was born in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] in 1966 and raised in [[Wolfville]], Nova Scotia.<ref name=\"parlbio\" /> He earned his bachelor's degree in history from [[Acadia University]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes2004/riding/298/ \"Canada Votes 2004: Vancouver Centre\"]. [[CBC News]].</ref>\n\nAfter moving to [[Burnaby, British Columbia]], in 1988, Stewart played bass guitar for the pop music band State of Mind.<ref>[https://vancouversun.com/news/wants+Commons+accept+online+petitions/7967681/story.html \"B.C. NDP MP wants commons to accept online petitions\"]. ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', February 14, 2013.</ref> In 1991, his band won three West Coast Music Awards.\n\nIn 1995, Stewart received his master's degree in political science from [[Simon Fraser University]], and a PhD in government from the [[London School of Economics]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.burnabynow.com/news/kennedy-stewart-to-succeed-siksay-for-the-ndp-in-burnaby-douglas-1.1900238 |title=Kennedy Stewart to succeed Siksay for the NDP in Burnaby-Douglas |work=[[Burnaby News Leader]] |date=February 28, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105021258/http://www.burnabynow.com/news/kennedy-stewart-to-succeed-siksay-for-the-ndp-in-burnaby-douglas-1.1900238 |archive-date=January 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAs an academic, Stewart has published research on citizen participation, democratic reform, and municipal governance.<ref name=\"parlbio\" /> His books include ''Local Government in Canada''.<ref>[http://www.hed.nelson.com/nelsonhed/instructor.do?product_isbn=9780176503963&topicid=5FFA&disciplinenumber=20&courseid=PO13&sortby=copy&type=all_radio&maintab=About_the_Book&subtab=Overview \"Local Government in Canada, 8th Edition\"]</ref>\n\nWhile serving as mayor, he is on leave from Simon Fraser University's School of Public Policy, where he teaches.<ref>[https://www.sfu.ca/mpp/faculty_and_associates/kennedy_stewart.html \"Kennedy Stewart\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502011611/http://www.sfu.ca/mpp/faculty_and_associates/kennedy_stewart.html# |date=May 2, 2014 }}. SFU School of Public Policy.</ref> Stewart's wife Jeanette Ashe also teaches politics, at [[Douglas College]].\n\n==Federal politics==\n\nOn March 28, 2004, Stewart won the nomination for the New Democratic Party for the federal riding of [[Vancouver Centre]] in a close three-way race. Although he lost in the [[2004 Canadian federal election|2004 general election]] by 4,230 votes, he increased the NDP's vote share in Vancouver Centre by 20 percentage points compared to the [[2000 Canadian federal election|2000 election]].\n\nOn February 25, 2011, Stewart secured the NDP nomination for the federal riding of Burnaby\u2014Douglas in a first ballot victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straight.com/article-376936/vancouver/kennedy-stewart-nominated-federal-ndp-candidate-burnabydouglas |title=Kennedy Stewart nominated as the federal NDP candidate in Burnaby-Douglas |work=[[Georgia Straight]] |date=February 26, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2015}}</ref> He won the riding in the [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011 general election]] with 44 percent of the vote, and was re-elected with 35 percent of the vote in 2015.\n\n===41st Parliament===\n\nIn 2012, NDP Leader [[Thomas Mulcair]] appointed Stewart as official opposition critic for science and technology and as a member of the standing committee on industry, science and technology. In Parliament, he opposed the Conservative government's elimination of the long-form census and funding cuts for basic scientific research.<ref>[http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/science \"NDP Science Critic\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222121206/http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/science# |date=December 22, 2015 }}. MP Website</ref> He tabled legislation (Motion 453) to protect scientific integrity in government departments and end the muzzling of federal scientists.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/members/Kennedy-Stewart(31701)/Motions?sessionId=151&documentId=6251254 \"Motion 453\"]. Parliament of Canada website</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Stewart introduced Bill C-558, The Parliamentary Science Officer Act. Following the elimination of Canada's National Science Advisor in 2008, the bill aimed to create an independent science watchdog tasked with providing Parliament with sound scientific information and ensuring decisions are informed by the best available evidence.<ref>[http://policyoptions.irpp.org/issues/clearing-the-air/stewart-cuddy/ \"Bringing Evidence Back to Palriament\"]. ''Policy Options'', July/August 2015</ref> Bill C-558 was endorsed by Evidence for Democracy, the Canadian Association of University Teachers, the Professional Institute of the Public Service of Canada, and the Centre for Science in the Public Interest.<ref>[http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/scientific-community-rallies-behind-ndp-proposal-for-independent-science-watchdog \"Science Community Rallies Behind NDP Proposal for Independent Science Watchdog\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222124408/http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/scientific-community-rallies-behind-ndp-proposal-for-independent-science-watchdog# |date=December 22, 2015 }}. Media Release</ref>\n\nStewart put forward a proposal (Motion 428) for the House of Commons to begin accepting petitions electronically as a means to engage more Canadians in the democratic process.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/members/Kennedy-Stewart(31701)/Motions?sessionId=151&documentId=6253259 \"Motion 428\"]. Parliament of Canada website</ref> It further proposed that short debates be triggered in Parliament if an online petition receives a significant number of signatures and is sponsored by at least five MPs. Stewart's proposal was endorsed by [[Ed Broadbent]], [[Preston Manning]], and a number of civil society groups.<ref>[https://vancouversun.com/news/Preston+Manning+Broadbent+find+common+ground/8014961/story.html  \"Preston Manning and Ed Broadbent find common ground\"]. ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', February 25, 2013.</ref> Being opposed by Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and his [[Conservative]] cabinet, Motion 428 passed the House of Commons by only two votes (142-140) on January 29, 2014.<ref>[https://openparliament.ca/votes/41-2/43/ \"Vote #43 on January 29th, 2014\"], Open Parliament.</ref> It was widely viewed as a \"surprise win\" for the official opposition.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/ndp-scores-surprise-win-on-e-petitions-thanks-to-8-tory-mps-1.2517292 \"NDP scores surprise win on e-petitions thanks to 8 Tory MPs\"], CBC News, January 20, 2014.</ref>\n\nStewart held public consultations with Burnaby residents on [[Kinder Morgan]]'s proposal to build a new export-only, bitumen-based crude oil pipeline through his riding.<ref>[http://www.burnabynewsleader.com/news/137683728.html \"72 percent of Burnaby-Douglas opposes Kinder Morgan pipeline expansion\"]. ''[[Burnaby News Leader]]'', January 19, 2012.</ref> Stewart became a vocal opponent of the project, citing community concerns over property expropriation, decreasing housing values, increased tanker traffic in the [[Burrard Inlet]], the use of temporary foreign workers, and the lack of benefits for British Columbia.<ref name=\"newsmaker\">{{cite web |url=http://www.burnabynow.com/news/newsmaker-of-the-year-kennedy-stewart-1.1901421 |title=Newsmaker of the Year: Kennedy Stewart |work=Burnaby News Leader |date=December 26, 2013 |access-date=December 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105021710/http://www.burnabynow.com/news/newsmaker-of-the-year-kennedy-stewart-1.1901421 |archive-date=January 5, 2016 }}</ref> His constituency office helped local residents sign-up to participate in the National Energy Board's review of the project.<ref>[http://www.vancouverobserver.com/environment/new-crude-oil-pipeline-your-neighborhood-mp-kennedy-stewart-tells-burnaby-constituents \"MP Kennedy Stewart wants Burnaby to have its say on Kinder Morgan pipeline\"]. ''[[Vancouver Observer]]'', January 24, 2014.</ref> In 2013, the ''Burnaby Newsleader'' named Stewart their \"Newsmaker of the Year\" for his community work on the Kinder Morgan pipeline.<ref name=\"newsmaker\" />\n\nStewart is an advocate for social housing and federal action to address BC's housing crisis.<ref>[http://www.burnabynow.com/news/mp-stewart-to-introduce-affordable-housing-strategy-1.1897236 \"MP Stewart to Introduced Affordable Housing Strategy\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222080356/http://www.burnabynow.com/news/mp-stewart-to-introduce-affordable-housing-strategy-1.1897236 |date=December 22, 2015 }}. ''[[Burnaby Now]]'', November 25, 2014.</ref> In 2014, he put forward a BC-specific affordable housing strategy (Motion 547) to recognize housing as a fundamental right, expand public investments in housing co-ops, maintain rent subsidies for low-income families, set targets for reducing and ending homelessness, and study the impact of investor speculation and housing vacancies on real estate prices.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/members/Kennedy-Stewart(31701)/Motions?sessionId=151&documentId=6799534 \"Motion 547\"]. Parliament of Canada website.</ref> His motion was endorsed by the City of Burnaby.<ref>[https://burnaby.civicweb.net/Documents/DocumentDisplay.aspx?Id=15676 \"Council Meeting Minutes\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. City of Burnaby, April 13, 2015.</ref>\n\n===42nd Parliament===\nHe was re-elected in the new riding of [[Burnaby South]] in the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]].\n\nFollowing the election, Stewart was re-appointed by Tom Mulcair as NDP critic for science.<ref>[https://www.ndp.ca/team \"NDP Shadow Cabinet\"]. NDP Website.</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2015, Parliament launched its new website for accepting electronic petitions from Canadians.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/about/house/newsroom/articles/2015-12-04-Advisory-b.pdf \"E-Petitions and Redesigned Committee Websites\"]. Parliament of Canada.</ref> Under the new system, initiated by Stewart's motion that passed before the election, the federal government has to respond within 45 days to online petitions if they are sponsored by one member of Parliament and receive at least 500 signatures.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/parliament-starts-accepting-e-petitions-this-week-1.3347526 \"Parliament Starts Accepting E-Petitions This Week\"]. CBC NEWS, December 2, 2015.</ref> Stewart sponsored the first official e-petition in Canada on behalf of two local constituents.<ref>[http://www.burnabynow.com/news/burnaby-couple-first-in-country-to-file-new-online-petition-1.2126624 \"Burnaby Couple First in Country to File New Online Petition\"]. ''Burnaby Now'', December 4, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2015, Stewart was elected by his caucus colleagues as chair of the NDP's British Columbia caucus.<ref name=\"caucuschair\">[https://www.facebook.com/notes/kennedy-stewart/ndp-elects-kennedy-stewart-as-bc-caucus-chair/927324534028120 \"NDP Elected Kennedy Stewart as BC Caucus Chair\"]. Media Release.</ref> In a statement, he vowed to support the NDP's newly elected MPs getting established in Parliament, strengthen engagement with stakeholders and constituents across the province, and hold the new Liberal government accountable for its election promises on affordable housing and pipeline reviews.<ref name=\"caucuschair\" />\n\n===2018 contempt of court===\n\nOn March 23, 2018, Stewart was arrested for [[civil contempt]] during a demonstration against the [[Trans Mountain Pipeline|Kinder Morgan pipeline]]. Other members of the demonstration, including fellow [[House of Commons of Canada|member of Parliament]] [[Elizabeth May]], were also arrested concerning the same incident. They were accused of violating a court order requiring those demonstrating to stay five metres back from company work sites, when they allegedly blocked the roadway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/elizabeth-may-kennedy-stewart-kinder-morgan-arrest-court-appearance-1.4611437 |title=Pipeline protesters including MPs Elizabeth May, Kennedy Stewart should face criminal charge: judge |last=Schmunk |first=Rhianna |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> On April 9, 2018, Justice Kenneth Affleck of the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]] recommended that Stewart and the others arrested should be charged with criminal contempt in relation to the alleged incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/news/judge-says-anti-pipline-protesters-including-elizabeth-may-should-face-criminal-contempt-charges/ |title=Elizabeth May, other anti-pipeline protesters should be criminally charged: judge |last=Slepian |first=Katya |work=[[Surrey Now-Leader]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/national/b-c-supreme-court-judge-calls-for-criminal-charges-against-elizabeth-may-and-trans-mountain-protesters/wcm/3d8ebe93-91f0-4fb5-b0bd-bd4123503678 |title=B.C. Supreme Court judge calls for criminal charges against Elizabeth May and Trans Mountain protesters |last=[[Canadian Press]] |work=[[Calgary Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/pipeline-protesters-including-green-leader-should-face-criminal-charges-judge-1.3877936 |title=Pipeline protesters including Green leader should face criminal charges: judge |last=Givetash |first=Linda |work=[[CTV News]]}}</ref> On April 16, 2018, it was reported that special prosecutors would be overseeing the charges against Stewart and May.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/special-prosecutors-to-handle-federal-mps-cases-after-anti-pipeline-protest-arrests-1.4621340 |title=Special prosecutors to handle federal MPs' cases after anti-pipeline protest arrests |last=Laanela |first=Mike |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> On May 14, 2018, Stewart pleaded guilty to criminal contempt of court for his actions during the protest and was fined $500. As criminal contempt is a [[Common law offence|common law]]\u2014not a [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]]\u2014offence, Stewart does not have a criminal record.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/kennedy-stewart-enters-guilty-plea-to-charge-of-criminal-contempt |title=MP Kennedy Stewart enters guilty plea to charge of criminal contempt for Kinder Morgan protest |last=Fraser |first=Keith |work=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/kennedy-stewart-pleads-guilty-to-criminal-contempt-for-kinder-morgan-protest-1.4662089 |title=Kennedy Stewart pleads guilty to criminal contempt for Kinder Morgan protest |last=CBC News |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n== Vancouver municipal politics ==\nStewart announced on May 10, 2018, that he will be resigning from Parliament in order to run to be the [[List of mayors of Vancouver|mayor of Vancouver]].<ref name=\"mayor\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Guly |first=Christopher |title=NDP MP Kennedy Stewart Leaving Federal Scene for Run as Vancouver's Mayor |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/11/Kennedy-Stewart-Vancouver-Mayor/ |work=[[The Tyee]]}}</ref> His resignation was effective September 14, 2018 (the last day he can file his paperwork to officially enter the mayoral race).<ref>{{cite tweet |user=kennedystewart |first=Kennedy |last=Stewart |number=1025145722289569792 |date=August 2, 2018 |title=As promised, I've submitted my resignation letter. I'll continue my MP duties until Sept 14 when I officially file as a #Vancouver mayoral candidate. It's been a great honour to serve my constituents for the last seven years. #ndp #vanpoli}}</ref> Until his resignation is official on September 14, Stewart told [[CBC News]] he intends to continue to campaign for mayor and collect his MP salary, saying that there is \"overlap\" between both roles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dickson |first=Janice |title=Kennedy Stewart says there's 'overlap' between his mayoral campaign and MP duties |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/stewart-mp-vancouver-salary-ndp-1.4816512 |work=[[CBC News]] |date=September 9, 2018}}</ref> On May 24, 2018, Stewart announced, if elected mayor, he would create a lobbyist registry and new conflict-of-interest rules for City Hall.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vancouver Courier |title=Mayoral candidate promises lobbyist registry, conflict-of-interest rules |url=http://www.vancourier.com/news/mayoral-candidate-promises-lobbyist-registry-conflict-of-interest-rules-1.23313289 |work=[[Vancouver Courier]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018 Vancouver municipal election]], Stewart was unofficially declared the winner of the mayoral race by a margin of fewer than 1000 votes over [[Non-Partisan Association|NPA]] candidate Ken Sim.<ref name=\":0\" /> Stewart is the first mayor of Vancouver to be unaffiliated with a municipal political party in over 30 years.<ref name=\"swearing in\" />\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|VAN|2018|List of mayors of Vancouver|Mayor of Vancouver|percent=yes}}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|[[Kennedy Stewart (Canadian politician)|Kennedy Stewart]]|49,705 |28.71 }}\n{{CANelec|VAN|NPA| Ken Sim| 48,748|28.16 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Shauna Sylvester| 35,457| 20.48}} \n{{CANelec|VAN|Coalition| [[Wai Young]]|11,872 |6.86 }}\n{{CANelec|VAN|YES|[[Hector Bremner]]|9,924 |5.73 }} \n{{CANelec|VAN|Van1st| Fred Harding| 5,640|3.26 }} \n{{CANelec|VAN|Pro|David Chen|3,573 |2.06 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Sean Cassidy|1,536|0.89 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|IDEA Vancouver|Connie Fogal|1,435|0.83 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Mike Hansen |951 |0.55 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Jason Lamarche |695 |0.40 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Rollergirl |686 |0.40 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Ping Chan | 653| 0.38}}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|John Yano | 510| 0.29}}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Tim Ly |349 |0.20 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Sophia C. Kaiser |336 |0.19 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Satwant K. Shottha |331 |0.19 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Lawrence Massey |233 |0.13 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Katy Le Rougetel |181 |0.10 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|G\u00f6l\u00f6k Z. Buday |178 |0.10 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Maynard Aubichon |139 |0.08 }}\n{{end}}\n{{Canadian federal election, 2015/Burnaby South}}\n{{CANelec/top|CA|2011|Burnaby\u2014Douglas|percent=yes|change=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Kennedy Stewart|20,943|42.99|+5.05}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Ronald Leung|19,932|40.92|+4.67}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Ken Low|5,451|11.19|-8.22}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Adrianne Merlo|1,754|3.60|-2.37}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Libertarian|Lewis Clarke Dahlby|420|0.86|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Communist|George Gidora|155|0.32|-0.11}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Marxist-Leninist|Brian Sproule|57|0.12|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes|48,710|100.0 &nbsp;}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|NDP|+0.19}}\n{{end}}\n{{CANelec/top|CA|2004|Vancouver Centre|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Hedy Fry]]|21,280|40.30|-2.00|$66,619}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Kennedy Stewart|17,050|32.29|+20.25|$57,675}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Gary Mitchell|10,139|19.20|-18.70|$73,789}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Robbie Mattu|3,580|6.78|+2.85|$2,440}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Libertarian|John Clarke|304|0.57|&ndash;|$60}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Joe Pal|243|0.46|&ndash;|$389}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Canadian Action|Alexander Frei|101|0.19|-1.08|$100}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Communist|Kimball Cariou|96|0.18|+0.01|$389}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes|52,793|100.0 &nbsp;}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total rejected ballots|226|0.43|-0.05}}\n{{CANelec/total|Turnout|53,019|61.47|0.97}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|-11.12}}\n{{CANelec/note|<small>Change for the Conservatives is based on the combined totals of the Canadian Alliance and the Progressive Conservatives.</small>}}\n{{End}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Canadian Parliament links|ID=17845|2=Kennedy Stewart}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140111040450/http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/ Kennedy Stewart - NDP Website]\n*[https://www.kennedystewart.ca/ Kennedy Stewart - Mayoral Campaign Website]\n\n{{Mayors of Vancouver|state=expanded}}\n{{Vancouver City Council|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Kennedy}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:New Democratic Party MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Simon Fraser University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Burnaby]]\n[[Category:Simon Fraser University faculty]]\n[[Category:Acadia University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian politician and academic}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox CanadianMP \n |honorific-prefix=[[His Worship]]\n| name= Kennedy Stewart\n| image = Kennedy-Stewart-MP.jpg\n|birth_name=Edward Charles Kennedy Stewart\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|11|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| profession= {{hlist|Politician|academic}}\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n| otherparty=[[New Democratic Party|New Democratic]]\n| party colour=\n| residence = [[Vancouver]], British Columbia\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Acadia University]]\n* [[Simon Fraser University]]\n* [[London School of Economics]]\n}}\n|office1= 40th [[Mayor of Vancouver]]\n|predecessor1=[[Gregor Robertson (politician)|Gregor Robertson]] \n|term_start1 = November 5, 2018\n| office2 = Member of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]]<br/>for [[Burnaby South]]\n| term_start2 = October 19, 2015\n| term_end2 = September 14, 2018\n| predecessor2= ''Riding established''\n| successor2=[[Jagmeet Singh]]\n| office3 = Member of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]]<br/>for [[Burnaby\u2014Douglas]]\n| term_start3 = May 2, 2011\n| term_end3 = October 19, 2015\n| predecessor3= [[Bill Siksay]]\n| successor3=''Riding dissolved''\n| office4 = NDP Science Critic\n| term_start4= June 19, 2012\n| term_end4= September 14, 2018\n| predecessor4= [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne LeBlanc]]\n| successor4= TBD\n\n| office5 = NDP BC Caucus Chair\n| term_start5= December 9, 2015\n| term_end5= September 14, 2018\n| predecessor5= [[Murray Rankin]]\n| successor5=TBD\n\n| spouse = Jeanette Ashe\n| website = {{URL|https://www.kennedystewart.ca/}}\n| footnotes=\n}}\n\n'''Edward Charles Kennedy Stewart''' (born November 8, 1966) is a Canadian politician and academic serving as the 40th and current [[List of mayors of Vancouver|mayor of Vancouver]] since 2018.<ref name=\"swearing in\">{{cite news |last1=Fumano |first1=Dan |title=Collegiality reigns as Vancouver's new council starts work |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/vancouvers-new-mayor-and-council-to-be-sworn-in-monday-afternoon |access-date=November 7, 2018 |work=Vancouver Sun |date=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-vancouver-mayor-kennedy-stewart-calls-for-ubc-subway-project-to-be-in/ \"Vancouver Mayor Kennedy Stewart calls for UBC subway project to be in service by 2030\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', January 23, 2019.</ref> He previously was the [[member of Parliament]] (MP) for the riding of [[Burnaby\u2014Douglas]] (2011\u20132015) and [[Burnaby South]] (2015\u20132018), serving in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] as a member of the [[New Democratic Party]] (NDP) caucus.<ref name=\"parlbio\">[http://www.parl.gc.ca/parlinfo/Files/Parliamentarian.aspx?Item=eb8710eb-e6dd-4c04-9d9a-60e7c8503565&Language=E&Section=ALL \"Kennedy Stewart bio\"]. Parliament of Canada Biography.</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Stewart announced his pending resignation from Parliament, in order to seek election as Mayor of Vancouver as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"mayor\">{{cite news |last=Laanela |first=Mike |title=Kennedy Stewart confirms he will run for mayor of Vancouver as independent |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/kennedy-stewart-running-for-vancouver-mayor-1.4657199 |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> In August 2018, he publicly released his letter to the Speaker of House, [[Geoff Regan]], confirming his resignation, effective September 14, 2018. During the [[2018 Vancouver municipal election]], Stewart was declared the winner of the mayoral race by a margin of fewer than 1,000 votes over Ken Sim, the [[Non-Partisan Association]] (NPA) candidate.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://vancouver.ca/your-government/election-results-2018-table.aspx |title=Election results - table |last=Vancouver |first=City of |date=October 20, 2018 |website=vancouver.ca |access-date=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nStewart was born in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] in 1966 and raised in [[Wolfville]], Nova Scotia.<ref name=\"parlbio\" /> He earned his bachelor's degree in history from [[Acadia University]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes2004/riding/298/ \"Canada Votes 2004: Vancouver Centre\"]. [[CBC News]].</ref>\n\nAfter moving to [[Burnaby, British Columbia]], in 1988, Stewart played bass guitar for the pop music band State of Mind.<ref>[https://vancouversun.com/news/wants+Commons+accept+online+petitions/7967681/story.html \"B.C. NDP MP wants commons to accept online petitions\"]. ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', February 14, 2013.</ref> In 1991, his band won three West Coast Music Awards.\n\nIn 1995, Stewart received his master's degree in political science from [[Simon Fraser University]], and a PhD in government from the [[London School of Economics]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.burnabynow.com/news/kennedy-stewart-to-succeed-siksay-for-the-ndp-in-burnaby-douglas-1.1900238 |title=Kennedy Stewart to succeed Siksay for the NDP in Burnaby-Douglas |work=[[Burnaby News Leader]] |date=February 28, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105021258/http://www.burnabynow.com/news/kennedy-stewart-to-succeed-siksay-for-the-ndp-in-burnaby-douglas-1.1900238 |archive-date=January 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAs an academic, Stewart has published research on citizen participation, democratic reform, and municipal governance.<ref name=\"parlbio\" /> His books include ''Local Government in Canada''.<ref>[http://www.hed.nelson.com/nelsonhed/instructor.do?product_isbn=9780176503963&topicid=5FFA&disciplinenumber=20&courseid=PO13&sortby=copy&type=all_radio&maintab=About_the_Book&subtab=Overview \"Local Government in Canada, 8th Edition\"]</ref>\n\nWhile serving as mayor, he is on leave from Simon Fraser University's School of Public Policy, where he teaches.<ref>[https://www.sfu.ca/mpp/faculty_and_associates/kennedy_stewart.html \"Kennedy Stewart\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502011611/http://www.sfu.ca/mpp/faculty_and_associates/kennedy_stewart.html# |date=May 2, 2014 }}. SFU School of Public Policy.</ref> Stewart's wife Jeanette Ashe also teaches politics, at [[Douglas College]].\n\n==Federal politics==\n\nOn March 28, 2004, Stewart won the nomination for the New Democratic Party for the federal riding of [[Vancouver Centre]] in a close three-way race. Although he lost in the [[2004 Canadian federal election|2004 general election]] by 4,230 votes, he increased the NDP's vote share in Vancouver Centre by 20 percentage points compared to the [[2000 Canadian federal election|2000 election]].\n\nOn February 25, 2011, Stewart secured the NDP nomination for the federal riding of Burnaby\u2014Douglas in a first ballot victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straight.com/article-376936/vancouver/kennedy-stewart-nominated-federal-ndp-candidate-burnabydouglas |title=Kennedy Stewart nominated as the federal NDP candidate in Burnaby-Douglas |work=[[Georgia Straight]] |date=February 26, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2015}}</ref> He won the riding in the [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011 general election]] with 44 percent of the vote, and was re-elected with 35 percent of the vote in 2015.\n\n===41st Parliament===\n\nIn 2012, NDP Leader [[Thomas Mulcair]] appointed Stewart as official opposition critic for science and technology and as a member of the standing committee on industry, science and technology. In Parliament, he opposed the Conservative government's elimination of the long-form census and funding cuts for basic scientific research.<ref>[http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/science \"NDP Science Critic\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222121206/http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/science# |date=December 22, 2015 }}. MP Website</ref> He tabled legislation (Motion 453) to protect scientific integrity in government departments and end the muzzling of federal scientists.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/members/Kennedy-Stewart(31701)/Motions?sessionId=151&documentId=6251254 \"Motion 453\"]. Parliament of Canada website</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Stewart introduced Bill C-558, The Parliamentary Science Officer Act. Following the elimination of Canada's National Science Advisor in 2008, the bill aimed to create an independent science watchdog tasked with providing Parliament with sound scientific information and ensuring decisions are informed by the best available evidence.<ref>[http://policyoptions.irpp.org/issues/clearing-the-air/stewart-cuddy/ \"Bringing Evidence Back to Palriament\"]. ''Policy Options'', July/August 2015</ref> Bill C-558 was endorsed by Evidence for Democracy, the Canadian Association of University Teachers, the Professional Institute of the Public Service of Canada, and the Centre for Science in the Public Interest.<ref>[http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/scientific-community-rallies-behind-ndp-proposal-for-independent-science-watchdog \"Science Community Rallies Behind NDP Proposal for Independent Science Watchdog\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222124408/http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/scientific-community-rallies-behind-ndp-proposal-for-independent-science-watchdog# |date=December 22, 2015 }}. Media Release</ref>\n\nStewart put forward a proposal (Motion 428) for the House of Commons to begin accepting petitions electronically as a means to engage more Canadians in the democratic process.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/members/Kennedy-Stewart(31701)/Motions?sessionId=151&documentId=6253259 \"Motion 428\"]. Parliament of Canada website</ref> It further proposed that short debates be triggered in Parliament if an online petition receives a significant number of signatures and is sponsored by at least five MPs. Stewart's proposal was endorsed by [[Ed Broadbent]], [[Preston Manning]], and a number of civil society groups.<ref>[https://vancouversun.com/news/Preston+Manning+Broadbent+find+common+ground/8014961/story.html  \"Preston Manning and Ed Broadbent find common ground\"]. ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', February 25, 2013.</ref> Being opposed by Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and his [[Conservative]] cabinet, Motion 428 passed the House of Commons by only two votes (142-140) on January 29, 2014.<ref>[https://openparliament.ca/votes/41-2/43/ \"Vote #43 on January 29th, 2014\"], Open Parliament.</ref> It was widely viewed as a \"surprise win\" for the official opposition.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/ndp-scores-surprise-win-on-e-petitions-thanks-to-8-tory-mps-1.2517292 \"NDP scores surprise win on e-petitions thanks to 8 Tory MPs\"], CBC News, January 20, 2014.</ref>\n\nStewart held public consultations with Burnaby residents on [[Kinder Morgan]]'s proposal to build a new export-only, bitumen-based crude oil pipeline through his riding.<ref>[http://www.burnabynewsleader.com/news/137683728.html \"72 percent of Burnaby-Douglas opposes Kinder Morgan pipeline expansion\"]. ''[[Burnaby News Leader]]'', January 19, 2012.</ref> Stewart became a vocal opponent of the project, citing community concerns over property expropriation, decreasing housing values, increased tanker traffic in the [[Burrard Inlet]], the use of temporary foreign workers, and the lack of benefits for British Columbia.<ref name=\"newsmaker\">{{cite web |url=http://www.burnabynow.com/news/newsmaker-of-the-year-kennedy-stewart-1.1901421 |title=Newsmaker of the Year: Kennedy Stewart |work=Burnaby News Leader |date=December 26, 2013 |access-date=December 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105021710/http://www.burnabynow.com/news/newsmaker-of-the-year-kennedy-stewart-1.1901421 |archive-date=January 5, 2016 }}</ref> His constituency office helped local residents sign-up to participate in the National Energy Board's review of the project.<ref>[http://www.vancouverobserver.com/environment/new-crude-oil-pipeline-your-neighborhood-mp-kennedy-stewart-tells-burnaby-constituents \"MP Kennedy Stewart wants Burnaby to have its say on Kinder Morgan pipeline\"]. ''[[Vancouver Observer]]'', January 24, 2014.</ref> In 2013, the ''Burnaby Newsleader'' named Stewart their \"Newsmaker of the Year\" for his community work on the Kinder Morgan pipeline.<ref name=\"newsmaker\" />\n\nStewart is an advocate for social housing and federal action to address BC's housing crisis.<ref>[http://www.burnabynow.com/news/mp-stewart-to-introduce-affordable-housing-strategy-1.1897236 \"MP Stewart to Introduced Affordable Housing Strategy\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222080356/http://www.burnabynow.com/news/mp-stewart-to-introduce-affordable-housing-strategy-1.1897236 |date=December 22, 2015 }}. ''[[Burnaby Now]]'', November 25, 2014.</ref> In 2014, he put forward a BC-specific affordable housing strategy (Motion 547) to recognize housing as a fundamental right, expand public investments in housing co-ops, maintain rent subsidies for low-income families, set targets for reducing and ending homelessness, and study the impact of investor speculation and housing vacancies on real estate prices.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/members/Kennedy-Stewart(31701)/Motions?sessionId=151&documentId=6799534 \"Motion 547\"]. Parliament of Canada website.</ref> His motion was endorsed by the City of Burnaby.<ref>[https://burnaby.civicweb.net/Documents/DocumentDisplay.aspx?Id=15676 \"Council Meeting Minutes\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. City of Burnaby, April 13, 2015.</ref>\n\n===42nd Parliament===\nHe was re-elected in the new riding of [[Burnaby South]] in the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]].\n\nFollowing the election, Stewart was re-appointed by Tom Mulcair as NDP critic for science.<ref>[https://www.ndp.ca/team \"NDP Shadow Cabinet\"]. NDP Website.</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2015, Parliament launched its new website for accepting electronic petitions from Canadians.<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/about/house/newsroom/articles/2015-12-04-Advisory-b.pdf \"E-Petitions and Redesigned Committee Websites\"]. Parliament of Canada.</ref> Under the new system, initiated by Stewart's motion that passed before the election, the federal government has to respond within 45 days to online petitions if they are sponsored by one member of Parliament and receive at least 500 signatures.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/parliament-starts-accepting-e-petitions-this-week-1.3347526 \"Parliament Starts Accepting E-Petitions This Week\"]. CBC NEWS, December 2, 2015.</ref> Stewart sponsored the first official e-petition in Canada on behalf of two local constituents.<ref>[http://www.burnabynow.com/news/burnaby-couple-first-in-country-to-file-new-online-petition-1.2126624 \"Burnaby Couple First in Country to File New Online Petition\"]. ''Burnaby Now'', December 4, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2015, Stewart was elected by his caucus colleagues as chair of the NDP's British Columbia caucus.<ref name=\"caucuschair\">[https://www.facebook.com/notes/kennedy-stewart/ndp-elects-kennedy-stewart-as-bc-caucus-chair/927324534028120 \"NDP Elected Kennedy Stewart as BC Caucus Chair\"]. Media Release.</ref> In a statement, he vowed to support the NDP's newly elected MPs getting established in Parliament, strengthen engagement with stakeholders and constituents across the province, and hold the new Liberal government accountable for its election promises on affordable housing and pipeline reviews.<ref name=\"caucuschair\" />\n\n===2018 contempt of court===\n\nOn March 23, 2018, Stewart was arrested for [[civil contempt]] during a demonstration against the [[Trans Mountain Pipeline|Kinder Morgan pipeline]]. Other members of the demonstration, including fellow [[House of Commons of Canada|member of Parliament]] [[Elizabeth May]], were also arrested concerning the same incident. They were accused of violating a court order requiring those demonstrating to stay five metres back from company work sites, when they allegedly blocked the roadway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/elizabeth-may-kennedy-stewart-kinder-morgan-arrest-court-appearance-1.4611437 |title=Pipeline protesters including MPs Elizabeth May, Kennedy Stewart should face criminal charge: judge |last=Schmunk |first=Rhianna |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> On April 9, 2018, Justice Kenneth Affleck of the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]] recommended that Stewart and the others arrested should be charged with criminal contempt in relation to the alleged incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/news/judge-says-anti-pipline-protesters-including-elizabeth-may-should-face-criminal-contempt-charges/ |title=Elizabeth May, other anti-pipeline protesters should be criminally charged: judge |last=Slepian |first=Katya |work=[[Surrey Now-Leader]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/national/b-c-supreme-court-judge-calls-for-criminal-charges-against-elizabeth-may-and-trans-mountain-protesters/wcm/3d8ebe93-91f0-4fb5-b0bd-bd4123503678 |title=B.C. Supreme Court judge calls for criminal charges against Elizabeth May and Trans Mountain protesters |last=[[Canadian Press]] |work=[[Calgary Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/pipeline-protesters-including-green-leader-should-face-criminal-charges-judge-1.3877936 |title=Pipeline protesters including Green leader should face criminal charges: judge |last=Givetash |first=Linda |work=[[CTV News]]}}</ref> On April 16, 2018, it was reported that special prosecutors would be overseeing the charges against Stewart and May.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/special-prosecutors-to-handle-federal-mps-cases-after-anti-pipeline-protest-arrests-1.4621340 |title=Special prosecutors to handle federal MPs' cases after anti-pipeline protest arrests |last=Laanela |first=Mike |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> On May 14, 2018, Stewart pleaded guilty to criminal contempt of court for his actions during the protest and was fined $500. As criminal contempt is a [[Common law offence|common law]]\u2014not a [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]]\u2014offence, Stewart does not have a criminal record.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/kennedy-stewart-enters-guilty-plea-to-charge-of-criminal-contempt |title=MP Kennedy Stewart enters guilty plea to charge of criminal contempt for Kinder Morgan protest |last=Fraser |first=Keith |work=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/kennedy-stewart-pleads-guilty-to-criminal-contempt-for-kinder-morgan-protest-1.4662089 |title=Kennedy Stewart pleads guilty to criminal contempt for Kinder Morgan protest |last=CBC News |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n== Vancouver municipal politics ==\nStewart announced on May 10, 2018, that he will be resigning from Parliament in order to run to be the [[List of mayors of Vancouver|mayor of Vancouver]].<ref name=\"mayor\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Guly |first=Christopher |title=NDP MP Kennedy Stewart Leaving Federal Scene for Run as Vancouver's Mayor |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/11/Kennedy-Stewart-Vancouver-Mayor/ |work=[[The Tyee]]}}</ref> His resignation was effective September 14, 2018 (the last day he can file his paperwork to officially enter the mayoral race).<ref>{{cite tweet |user=kennedystewart |first=Kennedy |last=Stewart |number=1025145722289569792 |date=August 2, 2018 |title=As promised, I've submitted my resignation letter. I'll continue my MP duties until Sept 14 when I officially file as a #Vancouver mayoral candidate. It's been a great honour to serve my constituents for the last seven years. #ndp #vanpoli}}</ref> Until his resignation is official on September 14, Stewart told [[CBC News]] he intends to continue to campaign for mayor and collect his MP salary, saying that there is \"overlap\" between both roles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dickson |first=Janice |title=Kennedy Stewart says there's 'overlap' between his mayoral campaign and MP duties |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/stewart-mp-vancouver-salary-ndp-1.4816512 |work=[[CBC News]] |date=September 9, 2018}}</ref> On May 24, 2018, Stewart announced, if elected mayor, he would create a lobbyist registry and new conflict-of-interest rules for City Hall.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vancouver Courier |title=Mayoral candidate promises lobbyist registry, conflict-of-interest rules |url=http://www.vancourier.com/news/mayoral-candidate-promises-lobbyist-registry-conflict-of-interest-rules-1.23313289 |work=[[Vancouver Courier]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018 Vancouver municipal election]], Stewart was unofficially declared the winner of the mayoral race by a margin of fewer than 1000 votes over [[Non-Partisan Association|NPA]] candidate Ken Sim.<ref name=\":0\" /> Stewart is the first mayor of Vancouver to be unaffiliated with a municipal political party in over 30 years.<ref name=\"swearing in\" />\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|VAN|2018|List of mayors of Vancouver|Mayor of Vancouver|percent=yes}}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|[[Kennedy Stewart (Canadian politician)|Kennedy Stewart]]|49,705 |28.71 }}\n{{CANelec|VAN|NPA| Ken Sim| 48,748|28.16 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Shauna Sylvester| 35,457| 20.48}} \n{{CANelec|VAN|Coalition| [[Wai Young]]|11,872 |6.86 }}\n{{CANelec|VAN|YES|[[Hector Bremner]]|9,924 |5.73 }} \n{{CANelec|VAN|Van1st| Fred Harding| 5,640|3.26 }} \n{{CANelec|VAN|Pro|David Chen|3,573 |2.06 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Sean Cassidy|1,536|0.89 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|IDEA Vancouver|Connie Fogal|1,435|0.83 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Mike Hansen |951 |0.55 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Jason Lamarche |695 |0.40 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Rollergirl |686 |0.40 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Ping Chan | 653| 0.38}}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|John Yano | 510| 0.29}}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Tim Ly |349 |0.20 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Sophia C. Kaiser |336 |0.19 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Satwant K. Shottha |331 |0.19 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Lawrence Massey |233 |0.13 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Katy Le Rougetel |181 |0.10 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|G\u00f6l\u00f6k Z. Buday |178 |0.10 }}\n{{CANelec|XX|Independent|Maynard Aubichon |139 |0.08 }}\n{{end}}\n{{Canadian federal election, 2015/Burnaby South}}\n{{CANelec/top|CA|2011|Burnaby\u2014Douglas|percent=yes|change=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Kennedy Stewart|20,943|42.99|+5.05}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Ronald Leung|19,932|40.92|+4.67}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Ken Low|5,451|11.19|-8.22}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Adrianne Merlo|1,754|3.60|-2.37}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Libertarian|Lewis Clarke Dahlby|420|0.86|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Communist|George Gidora|155|0.32|-0.11}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Marxist-Leninist|Brian Sproule|57|0.12|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes|48,710|100.0 &nbsp;}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|NDP|+0.19}}\n{{end}}\n{{CANelec/top|CA|2004|Vancouver Centre|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Hedy Fry]]|21,280|40.30|-2.00|$66,619}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Kennedy Stewart|17,050|32.29|+20.25|$57,675}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Gary Mitchell|10,139|19.20|-18.70|$73,789}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Robbie Mattu|3,580|6.78|+2.85|$2,440}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Libertarian|John Clarke|304|0.57|&ndash;|$60}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Joe Pal|243|0.46|&ndash;|$389}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Canadian Action|Alexander Frei|101|0.19|-1.08|$100}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Communist|Kimball Cariou|96|0.18|+0.01|$389}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes|52,793|100.0 &nbsp;}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total rejected ballots|226|0.43|-0.05}}\n{{CANelec/total|Turnout|53,019|61.47|0.97}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|-11.12}}\n{{CANelec/note|<small>Change for the Conservatives is based on the combined totals of the Canadian Alliance and the Progressive Conservatives.</small>}}\n{{End}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Canadian Parliament links|ID=17845|2=Kennedy Stewart}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140111040450/http://kennedystewart.ndp.ca/ Kennedy Stewart - NDP Website]\n*[https://www.kennedystewart.ca/ Kennedy Stewart - Mayoral Campaign Website]\n\n{{Mayors of Vancouver|state=expanded}}\n{{Vancouver City Council|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Kennedy}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:New Democratic Party MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Simon Fraser University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Burnaby]]\n[[Category:Simon Fraser University faculty]]\n[[Category:Acadia University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Vancouver]]\n", "name_user": "CentreLeftRight", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kennedy_Stewart_(Canadian_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Richard Ottaway", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{update|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Sir Richard Ottaway\n|image            = Richard Ottaway MP.jpg\n|office           = Chair of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]]\n|term_start       = 17 May 2010\n|term_end         = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor      = [[Mike Gapes]]\n|successor        = [[Crispin Blunt]]\n|office1          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Shadow Secretary of State for the Environment]]\n|leader1          = [[Michael Howard]]\n|term_start1      = 15 March 2004\n|term_end1        = 10 May 2005\n|predecessor1     = [[Caroline Spelman]]\n|successor1       = [[Oliver Letwin]] {{small|(Environment, Food and Rural Affairs)}}\n|office2 = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2 = [[John Major]]\n|term_start2 = 23 July 1996\n|term_end2 = 1 May 1997\n|predecessor2 = [[Derek Conway]]\n|successor2 = [[Jim Dowd (politician)|Jim Dowd]]\n|office3         = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Croydon South (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon South]]\n|term_start3      = 9 April 1992\n|term_end3        = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor3     = [[William Clark, Baron Clark of Kempston|William Clark]]\n|successor3       = [[Chris Philp]]\n|office4          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]]\n|term_start4      = 9 June 1983\n|term_end4        = 11 June 1987\n|predecessor4     = [[William Whitlock (politician)|William Whitlock]]\n|successor4       = [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1945|5|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Sonning]], [[England]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = Nicola Ottaway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/110124/part2.htm |title=House of Commons - The Register of Members' Financial Interests - Part 2: Part 2 |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n|alma_mater       = [[Britannia Royal Naval College]]<br />[[University of Bristol]]\n|allegiance       = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch           = {{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears     = 1961\u20131970\n|rank             = [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]\n}}\n'''Sir Richard Geoffrey James Ottaway''' (born 24 May 1945) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and most recently, was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Croydon South (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon South]] from 1992 to 2015. He was previously MP for [[Nottingham North]] (1983\u201387).\n\n==Early life==\nOttaway was born in Sonning, Berkshire. He attended [[Backwell School]], a secondary modern in [[Backwell]], [[North Somerset]], and joined the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] in [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] before serving as a [[Royal Navy]] officer in 1961-70 as a [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]].\n\nOttaway studied law at [[Bristol University]], graduating in 1974. He qualified as a solicitor in 1977, specialising in maritime and commercial law, and was a partner of William A. Crump & Son in London in 1981\u201387. He was a director of Coastal States Petroleum (UK) Ltd in 1988\u201395.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nOttaway was MP for Nottingham North from 1983 to 1987. This was a long-standing [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] seat, and he won it unexpectedly with a majority of 362 in the landslide victory following the [[Falklands War]]. Unsurprisingly the seat reverted to Labour in 1987, when he was defeated by [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]]. Ottaway re-entered Parliament in 1992 when he won Croydon South.\n\nIn 1992-95 Ottaway was Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[Michael Heseltine]] MP and from October 1995 he was a Government Whip. In opposition until 2005, he was a Front Bench spokesman as Shadow Minister for London and Local Government, Shadow Defence Minister, Shadow Paymaster General and Shadow Secretary of State for the Environment.\n\nIn the 2005\u20132010 Parliament he was a member of the [[Intelligence and Security Committee]], Vice Chairman of the [[1922 Committee]] and a member of the Conservative Party Board. After the 2010 election he became the first Chairman of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] to be elected by MPs from all sides of the House.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2010/06/11/feature-crib-sheet-to-britain-s-new-select-co |title=Feature: Crib sheet to Britain's new select committees |publisher=Politics.co.uk |date=11 June 2010 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 he was declared [[The Week|The Week's]] Back Bencher of the year based on an enquiry into [[Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/foreign-affairs-committee/inquiries1/afghanistan-and-pakistan/ |title=UK's foreign policy approach to Afghanistan and Pakistan - UK Parliament |publisher=Parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> that was highly critical of Government policy and urged the UK to do more to encourage the US to talk with the Taliban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/politics/politics/43726/ottaway-moles-backbencher-year-afghan-alert |title=Ottaway is Mole's backbencher of the year for Afghan alert &#124; News &#124; The Week UK |publisher=Theweek.co.uk |date=19 December 2011 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOttaway chaired the All Party Parliamentary London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Group and is a member of the All Party Parliamentary Group for Population, Development and Reproductive Health. In 2012 he won the Population Institute\u2019s Global Media Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.populationinstitute.org/newsroom/news/view/53/ |title=The Population Institute |publisher=The Population Institute |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> for ground-breaking research into population growth. His Sex, Ideology and Religion: 10 Myths about world population<ref>http://www.appg-popdevrh.org.uk/Richard%20Ottaway%20MP%20Paper%20on%20Population%20Growth%20-%2010%20Myths%20low%20res.doc.pdf</ref> won the Best Essay category.\n\nAs a long-standing campaigner for the right of terminally-ill people to die at home, Ottaway tabled a historic backbench committee debate on assisted suicide in the House of Commons in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201212/cmhansrd/cm120327/debtext/120327-0002.htm#12032752000001 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 27 Mar 2012 (pt 0002) |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> This resulted in Parliament agreeing for the first time that it is not in the public interest to prosecute people who compassionately help a loved one to die. However, assisting suicide is still illegal and the issue is highly controversial. He has subsequently made the case for assisted dying - suicide with the help of medical professionals. In October 2012 he debated at the Oxford Union in favour of the motion: This House Would Legalise Assisted Dying, and won by 167 to 131 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUAp-Pc088s |title=Richard Ottaway MP &#124; Assisted Dying SHOULD be legalised |publisher=YouTube |date=13 December 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Ottaway announced his decision not to stand in 2015 at a meeting of his local party.<ref>{{cite news |author=Glenn Ebrey |url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/BREAKING-NEWS-Croydon-South-MP-Richard-Ottaway/story-17189852-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505160515/http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/BREAKING-NEWS-Croydon-South-MP-Richard-Ottaway/story-17189852-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |title=Croydon South MP Richard Ottaway to stand down at 2015 General Election &#124; Croydon Advertiser |publisher=Thisiscroydontoday.co.uk |date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2014 }}</ref> He was appointed to the Privy Council in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Prime Minister's Office, 10 Downing Street |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/richard-ottaway-mp-approved-as-privy-councillor |title=Richard Ottaway MP approved as Privy Councillor - Press releases |publisher=GOV.UK |date=9 October 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> On 12 November 2013, [[Chris Philp]] was selected to become the next Conservative parliamentary candidate for Croydon South.\n\nOttaway was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the 2014 New Year Honours for parliamentary and political service.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60728|supp=y|page=1|date=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Affairs Select Committee===\nAfter the 2010 General Election Ottaway was elected the Chairman of the House of Commons Select Committee on Foreign Affairs. He has presided over inquiries including an annual look at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office\u2019s Human Rights work, the UK\u2019s relations with Saudi Arabia and Bahrain, foreign policy implications of and for a separate Scotland, and the future of the EU. He has raised through correspondence with Foreign Secretary William Hague concerns about the legality of arming rebels in Syria.\n\nOttaway voted for the [[Iraq War]] based on evidence presented to Parliament, but subsequently regretted his decision as he believes that the British public were not told the truth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/26023/political-profile-richard-ottaway.thtml |title=Political profile: Richard Ottaway |publisher=Total Politics |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203175211/http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/26023/political-profile-richard-ottaway.thtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ottaway was a member of the Foreign Affairs Committee in 2003 when the committee took evidence from [[David Kelly (weapons expert)|David Kelly]], the former UN weapons inspector who revealed details of the dossier on [[weapons of mass destruction]] in Iraq. His question to Prime Minister Tony Blair on 4 February 2003<ref>{{cite web|author=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons, Westminster |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo040204/debtext/40204-06.htm#40204-06_spnew5 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 4 Feb 2004 (pt 6) |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=4 February 2004 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> revealed that Blair had not appreciated that Iraq possessed only defensive battlefield or small-calibre weaponry rather than long-range weapons of mass destruction when he made his speech in the [[Iraq debate]] that led to the House of Commons voting in favour of war. Ottaway asserted that if that information had been spelled out to MPs \u201cthose weapons might not have been described as weapons of mass destruction threatening the region and the stability of the world\u201d. He is currently leading an inquiry on the UK's relation with [[Hong Kong]], a former British colony, 30 years after the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration|Joint Declaration]] amid series pro-democracy protests.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/foreign-affairs-committee/inquiries1/parliament-2010/hong-kong/ | title=The UK's relations with Hong Kong: 30 years after the Joint Declaration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2014/december/emergency-commons-debate-on-the-ban-by-china-on-the-foreign-affairs-committee-visit-to-hong-kong/ | title=Emergency debate on ban by China on Foreign Affairs Committee visit to Hong Kong - News from Parliament}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nOttaway is a founding member of the European Mainstream Group,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ft.com/westminster/2013/02/the-grand-launch-of-the-torys-pro-european-group/ |title=The grand launch of the Tories' pro-European group &#124; Westminster blog |publisher=Blogs.ft.com |date=14 February 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> formed in February 2013 to articulate a positive Conservative attitude to Europe as set out by [[David Cameron]] in his Bloomberg Speech.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/eu-speech-at-bloomberg |title=EU speech at Bloomberg - Speeches |publisher=GOV.UK |date=23 January 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> He supports the UK remaining in the EU, in a renegotiated relationship.\n\nAs Chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee, Ottaway presided over an inquiry into the Future of the EU<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/foreign-affairs-committee/inquiries1/parliament-2010/future-of-european-union-uk-government-policy/ |title=The future of the European Union: UK Government policy - UK Parliament |publisher=Parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> and has pledged his support for the EU Referendum Bill.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1178 |title=Richard Ottaway MP - News Story |publisher=Richardottaway.com |date=17 June 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202202908/http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1178 |archivedate=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 15 May 2013 he made the economic case for staying in the EU in the Queen\u2019s Speech debate on economic growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm130515/debtext/130515-0002.htm#13051532000481 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 15 May 2013 (pt 0002) |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> He answered his main opponent on the day in an article in [[ConservativeHome]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Ottaway MP |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2013/05/richard-ottaway-mp.html |title=Richard Ottaway MP: To the colleagues who heckled me, I say: it is in our national interest to stay in the E.U |publisher=Conservativehome.blogs.com |date=29 May 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===[[Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013]]===\nIn 2013, Ottaway celebrated the passing of his [[Private Member\u2019s Bill]] to crack down on metal theft and the desecration of war memorials<ref>http://www.warmemorials.org/uploads/publications/354.pdf</ref> by tighter regulation of scrap metal yards, car breakers and anyone buying, selling and trading in scrap metal. Ottoway worked closely with the Home Office, Chief Constable Paul Crowther and Superintendent John McBride to bring about change.  His interest in metal theft dated back to 2009, when thieves stole lead from a constituency parish church, causing tens of thousands of pounds worth damage to the building and the historic organ when rainwater trickled through.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1013 |title=Richard Ottaway MP - News Story |publisher=Richardottaway.com |date=21 January 2009 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202202754/http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1013 |archivedate=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Bill<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/10/enacted |title=Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 |publisher=Legislation.gov.uk |date=28 February 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> won overwhelming support in both Houses as well as from the Government. It was backed by organisations including [[The Royal British Legion]], [[War Memorials Trust]], [[Church of England]], [[Network Rail]], [[BT Group|BT]], the [[Energy Networks Association (United Kingdom)|Energy Networks Association]], the [[Institute of Directors]], the [[Federation of Small Businesses]], [[Arts Council England]], [[Tate Galleries]], the [[Henry Moore Foundation]], the [[Local Government Association]], [[British Transport Police]] and the [[British Metals Recycling Association]]. It received Royal Assent on 28 February 2013 and was implemented on 1 October 2013, in time for the centenary of the outbreak of the [[First World War]].\n\n===2009 expenses scandal===\nDuring the [[United Kingdom Parliamentary expenses scandal|''Daily Telegraph'' expenses scandal]] it was revealed that Ottaway claimed for a second home nine miles south of the constituency, with another house minutes from Parliament. Ottaway apologised to constituents for his part in 'allowing an indefensible system of allowances to develop'<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1023 |title=Richard Ottaway MP - News Story |publisher=Richardottaway.com |date=22 May 2009 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103045657/http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1023 |archivedate=3 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and announced he would let Croydon South party members decide his fate in a vote of confidence. The local association's President, [[Lord Bowness]], chaired the meeting, which ended in a secret ballot that Ottaway won.\n\nAmong his expenses claims between April 2004 and March 2008 were \u00a359.99 on light bulbs and \u00a348 for modifying a scarifier. He paid back \u00a32,025 that he had claimed as half of the price of an orthopaedic bed and \u00a31,400 for homeware and electrical goods. [[David Cameron|David Cameron\u2019s]] Conservative head office scrutiny panel did not ask him to pay back any more.\n\n===2014 Non-binding House of Commons vote on recognising the State of Palestine===\nOttaway voted in favour of recognition.\n\n==Refusal to meet with constituents==\n\nIt was reported that Ottaway called the police for 'security' when a group of constituents - most of whom were of pension age - visited his office to hand in a petition against the 'Gagging Law' (Transparency of Lobbying, non-Party Campaigning, and Trade Union Administration Bill) on 17 January 2014. A Metropolitan Police spokesman said: \u201cOfficers spoke to all parties. No offences were identified and the officers left.\u201d The MP, however, is reported as saying that he would do the same again.<ref>Tory MP called police for 'security' as pensioner volunteers delivered petition to office, https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/tory-mp-called-police-for-security-as-pensioner-volunteers-delivered-petition-to-office-9077000.html</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOttaway married Nicky, a magistrate and former international television production executive, in 1982. His main leisure interests are jazz and sailing. He is an active member of the [[All Party Parliamentary Jazz Appreciation Group]]. He is also a successful yachtsman and has won a number of amateur trophies.\n\nHe is the nephew of the actor [[James Ottaway]].\n\nIn 2015, he will accept the position of President of Croydon District Scout Council, having been a cub and scout himself in younger life.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050607065730/http://www.richardottaway.com/ Richard Ottaway MP] Official site\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-richard-ottaway | Richard Ottaway }}\n* [http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Richard+Ottaway/ ePolitix.com - Richard Ottaway MP]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-4006,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Richard Ottaway MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/richard_ottaway/croydon_south TheyWorkForYou.com - Richard Ottaway MP]\n* [http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Richard_Ottaway&mpc=Croydon+South The Public Whip - Richard Ottaway MP] voting record\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/171.stm BBC News - Richard Ottaway] profile BBC News, 16 March 2006\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Whitlock (politician)|William Whitlock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]]|years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Clark, Baron Clark of Kempston|William Clark]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Croydon South (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon South]]|years=[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Philp]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Gapes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee|Foreign Affairs Committee]]|years=2010\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=TBD}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Caroline Spelman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Shadow Secretary of State for the Environment]]|years=2004\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Oliver Letwin]]|as=Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ottaway, Richard}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English solicitors]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Backwell]]\n[[Category:People from Sonning]]\n[[Category:Politics of the London Borough of Croydon]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{update|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Sir Richard Ottaway\n|image            = Richard Ottaway MP.jpg\n|office           = Chair of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]]\n|term_start       = 17 May 2010\n|term_end         = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor      = [[Mike Gapes]]\n|successor        = [[Crispin Blunt]]\n|office1          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Shadow Secretary of State for the Environment]]\n|leader1          = [[Michael Howard]]\n|term_start1      = 15 March 2004\n|term_end1        = 10 May 2005\n|predecessor1     = [[Caroline Spelman]]\n|successor1       = [[Oliver Letwin]] {{small|(Environment, Food and Rural Affairs)}}\n|office2 = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2 = [[John Major]]\n|term_start2 = 23 July 1996\n|term_end2 = 1 May 1997\n|predecessor2 = [[Derek Conway]]\n|successor2 = [[Jim Dowd (politician)|Jim Dowd]]\n|office3         = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Croydon South (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon South]]\n|term_start3      = 9 April 1992\n|term_end3        = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor3     = [[William Clark, Baron Clark of Kempston|William Clark]]\n|successor3       = [[Chris Philp]]\n|office4          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]]\n|term_start4      = 9 June 1983\n|term_end4        = 11 June 1987\n|predecessor4     = [[William Whitlock (politician)|William Whitlock]]\n|successor4       = [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1945|5|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Sonning]], [[England]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = Nicola Ottaway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/110124/part2.htm |title=House of Commons - The Register of Members' Financial Interests - Part 2: Part 2 |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n|alma_mater       = [[Britannia Royal Naval College]]<br />[[University of Bristol]]\n|allegiance       = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch           = {{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears     = 1961\u20131970\n|rank             = [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]\n}}\n'''Sir Richard Geoffrey James Ottaway''' (born 24 May 1945) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and most recently, was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Croydon South (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon South]] from 1992 to 2015. He was previously MP for [[Nottingham North]] (1983\u201387).\n\n==Early life==\nOttaway was born in Sonning, Berkshire. He attended [[Backwell School]], a secondary modern in [[Backwell]], [[North Somerset]], and joined the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] in [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] before serving as a [[Royal Navy]] officer in 1961-70 as a [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]].\n\nOttaway studied law at [[Bristol University]], graduating in 1974. He qualified as a solicitor in 1977, specialising in maritime and commercial law, and was a partner of William A. Crump & Son in London in 1981-87. He was a director of Coastal States Petroleum (UK) Ltd in 1988-95.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nOttaway was MP for Nottingham North from 1983 to 1987. This was a long-standing [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] seat, and he won it unexpectedly with a majority of 362 in the landslide victory following the [[Falklands War]]. Unsurprisingly the seat reverted to Labour in 1987, when he was defeated by [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]]. Ottaway re-entered Parliament in 1992 when he won Croydon South.\n\nIn 1992-95 Ottaway was Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[Michael Heseltine]] MP and from October 1995 he was a Government Whip. In opposition until 2005, he was a Front Bench spokesman as Shadow Minister for London and Local Government, Shadow Defence Minister, Shadow Paymaster General and Shadow Secretary of State for the Environment.\n\nIn the 2005\u20132010 Parliament he was a member of the [[Intelligence and Security Committee]], Vice Chairman of the [[1922 Committee]] and a member of the Conservative Party Board. After the 2010 election he became the first Chairman of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] to be elected by MPs from all sides of the House.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2010/06/11/feature-crib-sheet-to-britain-s-new-select-co |title=Feature: Crib sheet to Britain's new select committees |publisher=Politics.co.uk |date=11 June 2010 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 he was declared [[The Week|The Week's]] Back Bencher of the year based on an enquiry into [[Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/foreign-affairs-committee/inquiries1/afghanistan-and-pakistan/ |title=UK's foreign policy approach to Afghanistan and Pakistan - UK Parliament |publisher=Parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> that was highly critical of Government policy and urged the UK to do more to encourage the US to talk with the Taliban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/politics/politics/43726/ottaway-moles-backbencher-year-afghan-alert |title=Ottaway is Mole's backbencher of the year for Afghan alert &#124; News &#124; The Week UK |publisher=Theweek.co.uk |date=19 December 2011 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOttaway chaired the All Party Parliamentary London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Group and is a member of the All Party Parliamentary Group for Population, Development and Reproductive Health. In 2012 he won the Population Institute\u2019s Global Media Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.populationinstitute.org/newsroom/news/view/53/ |title=The Population Institute |publisher=The Population Institute |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> for ground-breaking research into population growth. His Sex, Ideology and Religion: 10 Myths about world population<ref>http://www.appg-popdevrh.org.uk/Richard%20Ottaway%20MP%20Paper%20on%20Population%20Growth%20-%2010%20Myths%20low%20res.doc.pdf</ref> won the Best Essay category.\n\nAs a long-standing campaigner for the right of terminally-ill people to die at home, Ottaway tabled a historic backbench committee debate on assisted suicide in the House of Commons in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201212/cmhansrd/cm120327/debtext/120327-0002.htm#12032752000001 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 27 Mar 2012 (pt 0002) |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> This resulted in Parliament agreeing for the first time that it is not in the public interest to prosecute people who compassionately help a loved one to die. However, assisting suicide is still illegal and the issue is highly controversial. He has subsequently made the case for assisted dying - suicide with the help of medical professionals. In October 2012 he debated at the Oxford Union in favour of the motion: This House Would Legalise Assisted Dying, and won by 167 to 131 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUAp-Pc088s |title=Richard Ottaway MP &#124; Assisted Dying SHOULD be legalised |publisher=YouTube |date=13 December 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Ottaway announced his decision not to stand in 2015 at a meeting of his local party.<ref>{{cite news |author=Glenn Ebrey |url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/BREAKING-NEWS-Croydon-South-MP-Richard-Ottaway/story-17189852-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505160515/http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/BREAKING-NEWS-Croydon-South-MP-Richard-Ottaway/story-17189852-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |title=Croydon South MP Richard Ottaway to stand down at 2015 General Election &#124; Croydon Advertiser |publisher=Thisiscroydontoday.co.uk |date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2014 }}</ref> He was appointed to the Privy Council in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Prime Minister's Office, 10 Downing Street |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/richard-ottaway-mp-approved-as-privy-councillor |title=Richard Ottaway MP approved as Privy Councillor - Press releases |publisher=GOV.UK |date=9 October 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> On 12 November 2013, [[Chris Philp]] was selected to become the next Conservative parliamentary candidate for Croydon South.\n\nOttaway was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the 2014 New Year Honours for parliamentary and political service.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60728|supp=y|page=1|date=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Affairs Select Committee===\nAfter the 2010 General Election Ottaway was elected the Chairman of the House of Commons Select Committee on Foreign Affairs. He has presided over inquiries including an annual look at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office\u2019s Human Rights work, the UK\u2019s relations with Saudi Arabia and Bahrain, foreign policy implications of and for a separate Scotland, and the future of the EU. He has raised through correspondence with Foreign Secretary William Hague concerns about the legality of arming rebels in Syria.\n\nOttaway voted for the [[Iraq War]] based on evidence presented to Parliament, but subsequently regretted his decision as he believes that the British public were not told the truth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/26023/political-profile-richard-ottaway.thtml |title=Political profile: Richard Ottaway |publisher=Total Politics |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203175211/http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/26023/political-profile-richard-ottaway.thtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ottaway was a member of the Foreign Affairs Committee in 2003 when the committee took evidence from [[David Kelly (weapons expert)|David Kelly]], the former UN weapons inspector who revealed details of the dossier on [[weapons of mass destruction]] in Iraq. His question to Prime Minister Tony Blair on 4 February 2003<ref>{{cite web|author=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons, Westminster |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo040204/debtext/40204-06.htm#40204-06_spnew5 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 4 Feb 2004 (pt 6) |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=4 February 2004 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> revealed that Blair had not appreciated that Iraq possessed only defensive battlefield or small-calibre weaponry rather than long-range weapons of mass destruction when he made his speech in the [[Iraq debate]] that led to the House of Commons voting in favour of war. Ottaway asserted that if that information had been spelled out to MPs \u201cthose weapons might not have been described as weapons of mass destruction threatening the region and the stability of the world\u201d. He is currently leading an inquiry on the UK's relation with [[Hong Kong]], a former British colony, 30 years after the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration|Joint Declaration]] amid series pro-democracy protests.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/foreign-affairs-committee/inquiries1/parliament-2010/hong-kong/ | title=The UK's relations with Hong Kong: 30 years after the Joint Declaration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2014/december/emergency-commons-debate-on-the-ban-by-china-on-the-foreign-affairs-committee-visit-to-hong-kong/ | title=Emergency debate on ban by China on Foreign Affairs Committee visit to Hong Kong - News from Parliament}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nOttaway is a founding member of the European Mainstream Group,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ft.com/westminster/2013/02/the-grand-launch-of-the-torys-pro-european-group/ |title=The grand launch of the Tories' pro-European group &#124; Westminster blog |publisher=Blogs.ft.com |date=14 February 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> formed in February 2013 to articulate a positive Conservative attitude to Europe as set out by [[David Cameron]] in his Bloomberg Speech.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/eu-speech-at-bloomberg |title=EU speech at Bloomberg - Speeches |publisher=GOV.UK |date=23 January 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> He supports the UK remaining in the EU, in a renegotiated relationship.\n\nAs Chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee, Ottaway presided over an inquiry into the Future of the EU<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/foreign-affairs-committee/inquiries1/parliament-2010/future-of-european-union-uk-government-policy/ |title=The future of the European Union: UK Government policy - UK Parliament |publisher=Parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> and has pledged his support for the EU Referendum Bill.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1178 |title=Richard Ottaway MP - News Story |publisher=Richardottaway.com |date=17 June 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202202908/http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1178 |archivedate=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 15 May 2013 he made the economic case for staying in the EU in the Queen\u2019s Speech debate on economic growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm130515/debtext/130515-0002.htm#13051532000481 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 15 May 2013 (pt 0002) |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> He answered his main opponent on the day in an article in [[ConservativeHome]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Ottaway MP |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2013/05/richard-ottaway-mp.html |title=Richard Ottaway MP: To the colleagues who heckled me, I say: it is in our national interest to stay in the E.U |publisher=Conservativehome.blogs.com |date=29 May 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===[[Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013]]===\nIn 2013, Ottaway celebrated the passing of his [[Private Member\u2019s Bill]] to crack down on metal theft and the desecration of war memorials<ref>http://www.warmemorials.org/uploads/publications/354.pdf</ref> by tighter regulation of scrap metal yards, car breakers and anyone buying, selling and trading in scrap metal. Ottoway worked closely with the Home Office, Chief Constable Paul Crowther and Superintendent John McBride to bring about change.  His interest in metal theft dated back to 2009, when thieves stole lead from a constituency parish church, causing tens of thousands of pounds worth damage to the building and the historic organ when rainwater trickled through.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1013 |title=Richard Ottaway MP - News Story |publisher=Richardottaway.com |date=21 January 2009 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202202754/http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1013 |archivedate=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Bill<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/10/enacted |title=Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 |publisher=Legislation.gov.uk |date=28 February 2013 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> won overwhelming support in both Houses as well as from the Government. It was backed by organisations including [[The Royal British Legion]], [[War Memorials Trust]], [[Church of England]], [[Network Rail]], [[BT Group|BT]], the [[Energy Networks Association (United Kingdom)|Energy Networks Association]], the [[Institute of Directors]], the [[Federation of Small Businesses]], [[Arts Council England]], [[Tate Galleries]], the [[Henry Moore Foundation]], the [[Local Government Association]], [[British Transport Police]] and the [[British Metals Recycling Association]]. It received Royal Assent on 28 February 2013 and was implemented on 1 October 2013, in time for the centenary of the outbreak of the [[First World War]].\n\n===2009 expenses scandal===\nDuring the [[United Kingdom Parliamentary expenses scandal|''Daily Telegraph'' expenses scandal]] it was revealed that Ottaway claimed for a second home nine miles south of the constituency, with another house minutes from Parliament. Ottaway apologised to constituents for his part in 'allowing an indefensible system of allowances to develop'<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1023 |title=Richard Ottaway MP - News Story |publisher=Richardottaway.com |date=22 May 2009 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103045657/http://www.richardottaway.com/news_detail.asp?StoryID=1023 |archivedate=3 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and announced he would let Croydon South party members decide his fate in a vote of confidence. The local association's President, [[Lord Bowness]], chaired the meeting, which ended in a secret ballot that Ottaway won.\n\nAmong his expenses claims between April 2004 and March 2008 were \u00a359.99 on light bulbs and \u00a348 for modifying a scarifier. He paid back \u00a32,025 that he had claimed as half of the price of an orthopaedic bed and \u00a31,400 for homeware and electrical goods. [[David Cameron|David Cameron\u2019s]] Conservative head office scrutiny panel did not ask him to pay back any more.\n\n===2014 Non-binding House of Commons vote on recognising the State of Palestine===\nOttaway voted in favour of recognition.\n\n==Refusal to meet with constituents==\n\nIt was reported that Ottaway called the police for 'security' when a group of constituents - most of whom were of pension age - visited his office to hand in a petition against the 'Gagging Law' (Transparency of Lobbying, non-Party Campaigning, and Trade Union Administration Bill) on 17 January 2014. A Metropolitan Police spokesman said: \u201cOfficers spoke to all parties. No offences were identified and the officers left.\u201d The MP, however, is reported as saying that he would do the same again.<ref>Tory MP called police for 'security' as pensioner volunteers delivered petition to office, https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/tory-mp-called-police-for-security-as-pensioner-volunteers-delivered-petition-to-office-9077000.html</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOttaway married Nicky, a magistrate and former international television production executive, in 1982. His main leisure interests are jazz and sailing. He is an active member of the [[All Party Parliamentary Jazz Appreciation Group]]. He is also a successful yachtsman and has won a number of amateur trophies.\n\nHe is the nephew of the actor [[James Ottaway]].\n\nIn 2015, he will accept the position of President of Croydon District Scout Council, having been a cub and scout himself in younger life.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050607065730/http://www.richardottaway.com/ Richard Ottaway MP] Official site\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-richard-ottaway | Richard Ottaway }}\n* [http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Richard+Ottaway/ ePolitix.com - Richard Ottaway MP]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-4006,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Richard Ottaway MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/richard_ottaway/croydon_south TheyWorkForYou.com - Richard Ottaway MP]\n* [http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Richard_Ottaway&mpc=Croydon+South The Public Whip - Richard Ottaway MP] voting record\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/171.stm BBC News - Richard Ottaway] profile BBC News, 16 March 2006\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Whitlock (politician)|William Whitlock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]]|years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Clark, Baron Clark of Kempston|William Clark]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Croydon South (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon South]]|years=[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Philp]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Gapes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee|Foreign Affairs Committee]]|years=2010\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=TBD}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Caroline Spelman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Shadow Secretary of State for the Environment]]|years=2004\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Oliver Letwin]]|as=Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ottaway, Richard}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English solicitors]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Backwell]]\n[[Category:People from Sonning]]\n[[Category:Politics of the London Borough of Croydon]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1981-87 \u2192 1981\u201387 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Ottaway"}
{"title_page": "Tameka Cottle", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tameka \"Tiny\" Harris\n| alias              = Tiny\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = Tameka Dianne Cottle\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1975|7|14}}\n| birth_place        = [[College Park, Georgia]], [[U.S.]]\n| residence          = [[Jonesboro, Georgia]], [[U.S.]]\n| height             = {{height|ft=4|in=11}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage| [[T.I. (rapper)|T.I.]]|2010}} (3 children)\n| partner            = Zonnie \"Zeboe\" Pullins (1992-1998; 1 child)\n| children           = 4\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer-songwriter\n* television personality\n}}\n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| module             = {{infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| genre = <!-- Main genres only! No subgenres --> {{flatlist|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]\n}}\n| instrument = [[Vocals]]\n| background = solo_singer  <!-- mandatory format: please do not change or remove -->\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment|Sony BMG]]\n* [[Grand Hustle]]\nEquity/ [[Roc Nation]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[T.I.]]\n* [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]]\n* [[OMG (group)|OMG]]\n* [[Kandi Burruss]]\n* [[Antonia Wright|Toya Wright]]\n* Shekinah Jo\n}}\n| website = {{URL|https://officialtinyharris.com|Official Website}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Tameka Dianne \"Tiny\" Harris''' (n\u00e9e '''Cottle'''; born July 14, 1975) is an [[United States of America|American]] [[singer-songwriter]] from [[Jonesboro, Georgia]]. Cottle rose to fame in the 1990s as a member of the American multi-platinum R&B vocal group [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]]. Cottle is also known for her marriage to rapper [[T.I.]]. Cottle received a [[Grammy Award]] for her writing contributions on the [[TLC (group)|TLC]] hit \"[[No Scrubs]]\". Cottle acquired the nickname \"Tiny\" due to her small stature of 4'11\".\n\n==Early life and career==\nCottle was born in [[College Park, Georgia]] to a [[European American]] mother, Dianne Cottle (b. 1945) and an [[African American]] father, Charles \"Speedy\" Pope (1936\u20132013). Cottle's father and her uncle, Joseph Pope (1933\u20131996), formed the R&B group [[The Tams]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Zell |title=They Heard Georgia Singing|publisher=Mercer University Press|year=1996|pages=285|isbn=0-86554-504-9}}</ref> Cottle joined the R&B [[quartet]] [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]] in 1992 while attending Tri-Cities Performing Arts High School. Xscape was discovered by producer [[Jermaine Dupri]] while singing at his birthday celebration in [[Atlanta]]. Dupri immediately signed the group to his then new record label, [[So So Def|So So Def Recordings]].\n\nAs a member of the group, Cottle has contributed to three of the band's platinum albums: ''[[Hummin' Comin' at 'Cha]]'', ''[[Off the Hook (Xscape album)|Off the Hook]]'', and ''[[Traces of My Lipstick]]''. As a member of Xscape, she has received two [[Soul Train Music Awards]] for Best New R&B Artist and Best R&B Album and the A-Town Music Award for Best Duo/Group. Cottle sang lead vocals on six of Xscape's hit singles: \"[[Understanding (song)|Understanding]]\", \"Do You Want To?\", \"All I Need\", \"Love's a Funny Thing\", \"My Little Secret\",  and \"Am I Dreamin'\". She has also recorded on soundtracks for ''[[Soul Food (film)|Soul Food]]'', ''[[Panther (film)|Panther]]'', ''[[Bad Boys (1995 film)|Bad Boys]]'', and ''[[Love Jones (film)|Love Jones]]''. In 1998, after the release of Xscape's third album, ''Traces of My Lipstick'', the band parted ways.\n\nIn 2000, Cottle and fellow former Xscape group member [[Kandi Burruss]] were honored with a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best R&B Song]] for penning [[TLC (band)|TLC]]'s hit single \"[[No Scrubs]]\". Cottle's other accomplishments include an [[ASCAP|American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] award in the R&B and Pop Music categories for \"No Scrubs\", as well as the ASCAP Rap Award for her work on the [[Sporty Thievz]] track \"[[No Pigeons]]\". Cottle has also worked with [[T.I.]], [[8Ball & MJG]], [[Lil' Kim]] and [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Bow Wow]].\n\nAfter a five-year hiatus, Cottle reunited with sisters LaTocha and Tamika Scott and added a new member, Kiesha Miles, to release a Xscape album entitled ''Unchained'' and released the single \"What's Up\" in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200503&listid=01|title=Xscape Breaks the Chains|last=Boston |first=Ericka |author2=Terrell, Calvin |publisher=s2smagazine.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311195711/http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200503&listid=01|archivedate=11 March 2005}}</ref>\n\nCottle is involved in a project with Kiesha Miles called the [[OMG Girlz]]. Cottle's daughter, Zonnique, is a part of the musical trio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205193111/http://www.qt-possie.com/index.php?pr=BIO|title=QT-Possie|date=December 5, 2006|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, Cottle's reality series, ''[[Tiny and Toya]]'', made its debut on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2009/07/09/tiny-toya-interviews/?cxntfid=blogs_radio_tv_talk|title=Tiny & Toya interviews about BET show|last=Ho|first=Rodney|date=July 9, 2009|publisher=ajc.com|accessdate=July 20, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724075047/http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2009/07/09/tiny-toya-interviews/?cxntfid=blogs_radio_tv_talk|archivedate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in her husband's video for \"[[Hello (T.I. song)|Hello]]\" along with their family and the [[OMG Girlz]].\n\nOn July 22, 2014, Tameka returned to the music industry under her new label Pretty Hustle, with her first solo single \"What The Fuck You Gon Do?\". Within a few hours of \"WTFYGD\" being released it reached the number 5 spot on the iTunes R&B/Soul charts, and less than 24 hours after release it became the number one song on the charts for the genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/news/music/2014/07/23/tiny-sends-a-message-to-t-i-on-wtfygd.html?cid=facebook|title=Tiny Sends a Message to T.I. on 'WTFYGD'|website=BET.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freddyo.com/tinys-new-single-wtfygd-hits-number-1-rbsoul-for-itunes-in-less-than-24-hours/|title=Tiny's New Single #WTFYGD Hits Number 1 R&B/Soul for iTunes in Less than 24 Hours!|date=July 23, 2014|website=FreddyO.com}}</ref>\n\nShe and bandmate [[Kandi Burruss]], also have writing credits on the song [[Shape of You]] by [[Ed Sheeran]].\n\nIn 2018, Tiny Harris took a break from her [[Xscape (group)|XSCAP3]] EP Promo to spend some quality time with her one-year-old daughter Heiress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2018/03/03/tiny-bonds-baby-heiress-new-video-watch-xscap3/|title=Tiny Harris Takes Break From Xscap3 EP Promo To Celebrate \u2018Sunshine\u2019 Baby Heiress \u2014 Video|last=Baumgartner|first=Scott|date=2018-03-04|work=Hollywood Life|access-date=2018-04-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2001, Cottle began dating rapper [[T.I.]]<ref name=\"T.I.: Me, Myself & I\">{{cite magazine|title=T.I.: Me, Myself & I |magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |date=July 23, 2007 |url=http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ |accessdate=October 31, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224075722/http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ |archivedate=December 24, 2007 }}</ref> Cottle and T.I. married on July 30, 2010 in [[Miami Beach, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1644852/20100731/t_i_.jhtml|title= T.I. And Tiny Marry In Three Cities|last= Ziegbe|first=Mawuse |date=July 31, 2010|publisher=mtv.com|accessdate=September 12, 2010}}</ref> They have two sons together: King Harris (born August 25, 2004), Major Philant Harris (born May 16, 2008) and a daughter, Heiress Diana Harris (born March 2016).<ref name=\"T.I.: Me, Myself & I\"/><ref name=\"Vibe\">[http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ T.I.: Me, Myself & I] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224075722/http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ |date=2007-12-24 }} ''Vibe''. Retrieved October 9, 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20200789,00.html |title=Rapper T.I. Welcomes His Second Son|last=Herndon|first=Jessica |date=May 16, 2008|publisher=people.com|accessdate=December 12, 2008}}</ref> Their first daughter was [[stillbirth|stillborn]] in 2007, six months into a complicated pregnancy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/tameka_tiny_cottle_interview_part_2/ |title=Tameka 'Tiny' Cottle: 'I Know My Man's Heart' |last=Byrd |first=Kenya N. |date=February 6, 2009 |publisher=essence.com (via archive.org) |accessdate=June 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215004010/http://www1.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/tameka_tiny_cottle_interview_part_2/ |archivedate=February 15, 2010 }}</ref> Cottle also has an older daughter from her previous relationship with Zonnie \"Zeboe\" Pullins.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_8_56/ai_75247881|title=Toni & Keril's Dream Wedding - singer Toni Braxton weds|last=Bennett Kinnon|first=Joy |date=June 2001 |work=Ebony |accessdate=December 13, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Who's Lovin' Who?|last=Cole|first=Harriette |date=February 2008  |work=Ebony |pages=75\u201376}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://tipharris-tameka.blogspot.com/2007/04/recnt-pic-of-zonnique.html |title=Zonnique & Her Biological Dad |publisher=Tipharris-tameka.blogspot.com |date=April 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 9, 2011}}</ref> Through her marriage to T.I., Cottle has three [[Stepfamily|stepchildren]].<ref name=\"People\">{{cite web|date=April 24, 2006|title=Hip-Hop Star & Actor T.I.|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20059205,00.html|accessdate=December 12, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 25, 2008|title=T.I. to pay ex $3,000 per month in child support|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|url=http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/39999|accessdate=December 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, ''[[T.I. & Tiny: The Family Hustle]]'' premiered on [[VH1]]. The series chronicles the lives of Cottle and T.I. plus their family.\n\nCottle's father, Charles Pope, died on July 11, 2013, at the age of 76 after a long battle with [[Alzheimer's Disease]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Doc Rock |url=http://www.thedeadrockstarsclub.com/2013b.html#sthash.KHCjFI7F.LKLrfZad.dpbs |title=July to December |publisher=The Dead Rock Stars Club |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"tdad\">{{cite web | url=http://s2smagazine.com/75894/tiny-harris-heartbroken-following-dads-death/ | title=Tiny Harris \u2018heartbroken\u2019 following dad\u2019s death | publisher=S2S Magazine | work=S2S Magazine | date=July 12, 2013 | accessdate=July 25, 2013 | author=Scott, Tracy | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715232251/http://s2smagazine.com/75894/tiny-harris-heartbroken-following-dads-death/ | archive-date=2013-07-15 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''Tiny and Shekinah's Weave Trip'' premiered on VH1 on October 13, 2014. The series chronicles Cottle and her best friend Shekinah Anderson in a mobile hair salon across the country.\n\nIn March 2016, the couple had a daughter.  In December 2016, Cottle filed for divorce from T.I. after six years of marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/music/tiny-harris-files-divorce-from-ti/|title=Tiny Harris Files for Divorce from Rapper Husband T.I. After Six Years of Marriage|date=2016-12-28|newspaper=People |access-date=2016-12-28}}</ref> However, the couple worked on healing their marriage in 2017 after Tiny spent time with her group Xscape, and Tiny dropped the divorce files stating: \"The divorce is off.\"<ref name=\"diholly\">{{cite web |last1=Shilliday |first1=Beth |title=Tiny Doesn\u2019t Regret Filing For Divorce From T.I.: It Changed Their Relationship For The Better |url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2018/10/12/ti-tiny-harris-divorce-saved-marriage-doesnt-regret-filing/ |website=Hollywood Life |accessdate=24 April 2019 |language=en |date=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"divblasta\">{{cite web |last1=Willis |first1=Kiersten |title=Tiny Breaks Her Silence About T.I.'s Cheating: 'Divorce Is Off But We're Still Living Separately' |url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2018/10/23/tiny-breaks-her-silence-about-t-i-s-cheating-divorce-is-off-but-were-still-living-separately/ |website=Atlanta Black Star |accessdate=24 April 2019 |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was announced she would own the Atlanta Heirs basketball team under the newly developed Global Mixed Gender Basketball league, which was founded by rapper [[Master P]]. Her team would be a part of its inaugural debut on September 23, 2017 in a neutral match at the [[Cox Pavilion]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] against Master P's own squad, the New Orleans Gators.\n\n===Legal issues===\nOn September 1, 2010, Cottle and T.I. were arrested following a motor vehicle stop in [[Los Angeles]]. The police reported that an odor of burnt marijuana was coming from the vehicle and the couple were found to be in possession of a controlled substance, ecstasy. They posted $10,000 bail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/Music/09/02/rapper.arrested/index.html?hpt=T2|title= Police: Rapper T.I. and wife arrested on drug suspicion|last= Allen|first=Duke|date=September 2, 2010 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=September 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or       |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.  Or submit your link    |\n    | to the appropriate category at the Open Directory Project (www.dmoz.org)|\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.             |\n===({{NoMoreLinks}})=======-->\n* {{Twitter|tinymajormama}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=2038081}}\n\n{{Xscape}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cottle, Tameka}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:T.I.]]\n[[Category:American soul musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Jonesboro, Georgia]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Tameka \"Tiny\" Harris\n| alias = Tiny \n| image =  \n| birth_name = Tameka Dianne Cottle \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|7|14}}\n| birth_place = [[College Park, Georgia]], [[U.S.]]\n| residence = [[Jonesboro, Georgia]], [[U.S.]]\n| height = {{height|ft=4|in=11}}\n| spouse = {{marriage| [[T.I. (rapper)|T.I.]]|2010}} (3 children)\n| partner = Zonnie \"Zeboe\" Pullins (1992-1998; 1 child)\n| children = 4\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Singer-songwriter\n* television personality\n}}\n| years_active = 1992\u2013present\n\n| module = {{infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| genre = <!-- Main genres only! No subgenres --> {{flatlist|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]\n}}\n| instrument = [[Vocals]]\n| background = solo_singer  <!-- mandatory format: please do not change or remove -->\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment|Sony BMG]]\n* [[Grand Hustle]]\nEquity/ [[Roc Nation]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[T.I.]]\n* [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]]\n* [[OMG (group)|OMG]]\n* [[Kandi Burruss]]\n* [[Antonia Wright|Toya Wright]]\n* Shekinah Jo\n}}\n| website = {{URL|https://officialtinyharris.com|Official Website}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Tameka Dianne \"Tiny\" Harris''' (n\u00e9e '''Cottle'''; born July 14, 1975) is an [[United States of America|American]] [[singer-songwriter]] from [[Jonesboro, Georgia]]. Cottle rose to fame in the 1990s as a member of the American multi-platinum R&B vocal group [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]]. Cottle is also known for her marriage to rapper [[T.I.]]. Cottle received a [[Grammy Award]] for her writing contributions on the [[TLC (group)|TLC]] hit \"[[No Scrubs]]\". Cottle acquired the nickname \"Tiny\" due to her small stature of 4'11\".\n\n==Early life and career==\nCottle was born in [[College Park, Georgia]] to a [[European American]] mother, Dianne Cottle (b. 1945) and an [[African American]] father, Charles \"Speedy\" Pope (1936\u20132013). Cottle's father and her uncle, Joseph Pope (1933\u20131996), formed the R&B group [[The Tams]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Zell |title=They Heard Georgia Singing|publisher=Mercer University Press|year=1996|pages=285|isbn=0-86554-504-9}}</ref> Cottle joined the R&B [[quartet]] [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]] in 1992 while attending Tri-Cities Performing Arts High School. Xscape was discovered by producer [[Jermaine Dupri]] while singing at his birthday celebration in [[Atlanta]]. Dupri immediately signed the group to his then new record label, [[So So Def|So So Def Recordings]].\n\nAs a member of the group, Cottle has contributed to three of the band's platinum albums: ''[[Hummin' Comin' at 'Cha]]'', ''[[Off the Hook (Xscape album)|Off the Hook]]'', and ''[[Traces of My Lipstick]]''. As a member of Xscape, she has received two [[Soul Train Music Awards]] for Best New R&B Artist and Best R&B Album and the A-Town Music Award for Best Duo/Group. Cottle sang lead vocals on six of Xscape's hit singles: \"[[Understanding (song)|Understanding]]\", \"Do You Want To?\", \"All I Need\", \"Love's a Funny Thing\", \"My Little Secret\",  and \"Am I Dreamin'\". She has also recorded on soundtracks for ''[[Soul Food (film)|Soul Food]]'', ''[[Panther (film)|Panther]]'', ''[[Bad Boys (1995 film)|Bad Boys]]'', and ''[[Love Jones (film)|Love Jones]]''. In 1998, after the release of Xscape's third album, ''Traces of My Lipstick'', the band parted ways.\n\nIn 2000, Cottle and fellow former Xscape group member [[Kandi Burruss]] were honored with a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best R&B Song]] for penning [[TLC (band)|TLC]]'s hit single \"[[No Scrubs]]\". Cottle's other accomplishments include an [[ASCAP|American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] award in the R&B and Pop Music categories for \"No Scrubs\", as well as the ASCAP Rap Award for her work on the [[Sporty Thievz]] track \"[[No Pigeons]]\". Cottle has also worked with [[T.I.]], [[8Ball & MJG]], [[Lil' Kim]] and [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Bow Wow]].\n\nAfter a five-year hiatus, Cottle reunited with sisters LaTocha and Tamika Scott and added a new member, Kiesha Miles, to release a Xscape album entitled ''Unchained'' and released the single \"What's Up\" in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200503&listid=01|title=Xscape Breaks the Chains|last=Boston |first=Ericka |author2=Terrell, Calvin |publisher=s2smagazine.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311195711/http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200503&listid=01|archivedate=11 March 2005}}</ref>\n\nCottle is involved in a project with Kiesha Miles called the [[OMG Girlz]]. Cottle's daughter, Zonnique, is a part of the musical trio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205193111/http://www.qt-possie.com/index.php?pr=BIO|title=QT-Possie|date=December 5, 2006|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, Cottle's reality series, ''[[Tiny and Toya]]'', made its debut on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2009/07/09/tiny-toya-interviews/?cxntfid=blogs_radio_tv_talk|title=Tiny & Toya interviews about BET show|last=Ho|first=Rodney|date=July 9, 2009|publisher=ajc.com|accessdate=July 20, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724075047/http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2009/07/09/tiny-toya-interviews/?cxntfid=blogs_radio_tv_talk|archivedate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in her husband's video for \"[[Hello (T.I. song)|Hello]]\" along with their family and the [[OMG Girlz]].\n\nOn July 22, 2014, Tameka returned to the music industry under her new label Pretty Hustle, with her first solo single \"What The Fuck You Gon Do?\". Within a few hours of \"WTFYGD\" being released it reached the number 5 spot on the iTunes R&B/Soul charts, and less than 24 hours after release it became the number one song on the charts for the genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/news/music/2014/07/23/tiny-sends-a-message-to-t-i-on-wtfygd.html?cid=facebook|title=Tiny Sends a Message to T.I. on 'WTFYGD'|website=BET.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freddyo.com/tinys-new-single-wtfygd-hits-number-1-rbsoul-for-itunes-in-less-than-24-hours/|title=Tiny's New Single #WTFYGD Hits Number 1 R&B/Soul for iTunes in Less than 24 Hours!|date=July 23, 2014|website=FreddyO.com}}</ref>\n\nShe and bandmate [[Kandi Burruss]], also have writing credits on the song [[Shape of You]] by [[Ed Sheeran]].\n\nIn 2018, Tiny Harris took a break from her [[Xscape (group)|XSCAP3]] EP Promo to spend some quality time with her one-year-old daughter Heiress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2018/03/03/tiny-bonds-baby-heiress-new-video-watch-xscap3/|title=Tiny Harris Takes Break From Xscap3 EP Promo To Celebrate \u2018Sunshine\u2019 Baby Heiress \u2014 Video|last=Baumgartner|first=Scott|date=2018-03-04|work=Hollywood Life|access-date=2018-04-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2001, Cottle began dating rapper [[T.I.]]<ref name=\"T.I.: Me, Myself & I\">{{cite magazine|title=T.I.: Me, Myself & I |magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |date=July 23, 2007 |url=http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ |accessdate=October 31, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224075722/http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ |archivedate=December 24, 2007 }}</ref> Cottle and T.I. married on July 30, 2010 in [[Miami Beach, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1644852/20100731/t_i_.jhtml|title= T.I. And Tiny Marry In Three Cities|last= Ziegbe|first=Mawuse |date=July 31, 2010|publisher=mtv.com|accessdate=September 12, 2010}}</ref> They have two sons together: King Harris (born August 25, 2004), Major Philant Harris (born May 16, 2008) and a daughter, Heiress Diana Harris (born March 2016).<ref name=\"T.I.: Me, Myself & I\"/><ref name=\"Vibe\">[http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ T.I.: Me, Myself & I] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224075722/http://www.vibe.com/news/cover_stories/2007/07/ti_august_2007/ |date=2007-12-24 }} ''Vibe''. Retrieved October 9, 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20200789,00.html |title=Rapper T.I. Welcomes His Second Son|last=Herndon|first=Jessica |date=May 16, 2008|publisher=people.com|accessdate=December 12, 2008}}</ref> Their first daughter was [[stillbirth|stillborn]] in 2007, six months into a complicated pregnancy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/tameka_tiny_cottle_interview_part_2/ |title=Tameka 'Tiny' Cottle: 'I Know My Man's Heart' |last=Byrd |first=Kenya N. |date=February 6, 2009 |publisher=essence.com (via archive.org) |accessdate=June 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215004010/http://www1.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/tameka_tiny_cottle_interview_part_2/ |archivedate=February 15, 2010 }}</ref> Cottle also has an older daughter from her previous relationship with Zonnie \"Zeboe\" Pullins.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_8_56/ai_75247881|title=Toni & Keril's Dream Wedding - singer Toni Braxton weds|last=Bennett Kinnon|first=Joy |date=June 2001 |work=Ebony |accessdate=December 13, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Who's Lovin' Who?|last=Cole|first=Harriette |date=February 2008  |work=Ebony |pages=75\u201376}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://tipharris-tameka.blogspot.com/2007/04/recnt-pic-of-zonnique.html |title=Zonnique & Her Biological Dad |publisher=Tipharris-tameka.blogspot.com |date=April 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 9, 2011}}</ref> Through her marriage to T.I., Cottle has three [[Stepfamily|stepchildren]].<ref name=\"People\">{{cite web|date=April 24, 2006|title=Hip-Hop Star & Actor T.I.|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20059205,00.html|accessdate=December 12, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 25, 2008|title=T.I. to pay ex $3,000 per month in child support|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|url=http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/39999|accessdate=December 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, ''[[T.I. & Tiny: The Family Hustle]]'' premiered on [[VH1]]. The series chronicles the lives of Cottle and T.I. plus their family.\n\nCottle's father, Charles Pope, died on July 11, 2013, at the age of 76 after a long battle with [[Alzheimer's Disease]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Doc Rock |url=http://www.thedeadrockstarsclub.com/2013b.html#sthash.KHCjFI7F.LKLrfZad.dpbs |title=July to December |publisher=The Dead Rock Stars Club |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"tdad\">{{cite web | url=http://s2smagazine.com/75894/tiny-harris-heartbroken-following-dads-death/ | title=Tiny Harris \u2018heartbroken\u2019 following dad\u2019s death | publisher=S2S Magazine | work=S2S Magazine | date=July 12, 2013 | accessdate=July 25, 2013 | author=Scott, Tracy | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715232251/http://s2smagazine.com/75894/tiny-harris-heartbroken-following-dads-death/ | archive-date=2013-07-15 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''Tiny and Shekinah's Weave Trip'' premiered on VH1 on October 13, 2014. The series chronicles Cottle and her best friend Shekinah Anderson in a mobile hair salon across the country.\n\nIn March 2016, the couple had a daughter.  In December 2016, Cottle filed for divorce from T.I. after six years of marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/music/tiny-harris-files-divorce-from-ti/|title=Tiny Harris Files for Divorce from Rapper Husband T.I. After Six Years of Marriage|date=2016-12-28|newspaper=People |access-date=2016-12-28}}</ref> However, the couple worked on healing their marriage in 2017 after Tiny spent time with her group Xscape, and Tiny dropped the divorce files stating: \"The divorce is off.\"<ref name=\"diholly\">{{cite web |last1=Shilliday |first1=Beth |title=Tiny Doesn\u2019t Regret Filing For Divorce From T.I.: It Changed Their Relationship For The Better |url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2018/10/12/ti-tiny-harris-divorce-saved-marriage-doesnt-regret-filing/ |website=Hollywood Life |accessdate=24 April 2019 |language=en |date=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"divblasta\">{{cite web |last1=Willis |first1=Kiersten |title=Tiny Breaks Her Silence About T.I.'s Cheating: 'Divorce Is Off But We're Still Living Separately' |url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2018/10/23/tiny-breaks-her-silence-about-t-i-s-cheating-divorce-is-off-but-were-still-living-separately/ |website=Atlanta Black Star |accessdate=24 April 2019 |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was announced she would own the Atlanta Heirs basketball team under the newly developed Global Mixed Gender Basketball league, which was founded by rapper [[Master P]]. Her team would be a part of its inaugural debut on September 23, 2017 in a neutral match at the [[Cox Pavilion]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] against Master P's own squad, the New Orleans Gators.\n\n===Legal issues===\nOn September 1, 2010, Cottle and T.I. were arrested following a motor vehicle stop in [[Los Angeles]]. The police reported that an odor of burnt marijuana was coming from the vehicle and the couple were found to be in possession of a controlled substance, ecstasy. They posted $10,000 bail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/Music/09/02/rapper.arrested/index.html?hpt=T2|title= Police: Rapper T.I. and wife arrested on drug suspicion|last= Allen|first=Duke|date=September 2, 2010 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=September 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please 